<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austin Powers Car, Speed Racer Sold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ind. (AP) -- An Austin Powers ''Shagmobile'' and a
prototype of the futuristic Mach 5 from the 1960s cartoon ''Speed
Racer'' were sold at auction for $225,000 to the founder of a Los
Angeles auto museum.
</P>
<P>
   The cars topped the list of celebrity wheels sold at the 30th
annual Kruse International Auto Auction, the company announced
Monday. More than 5,000 vehicle were to be auctioned off during the
weeklong event, which ends Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other vehicles: The 1990 Chevrolet Lumina driven by
Tom Cruise in the movie ''Days of Thunder'' sold for $38,000, a
bulletproof Chevrolet Suburban made for Sylvester Stallone went for
$31,500, and Kentucky Fried Chicken founder Colonel Harland
Sanders' 1939 Lincoln limousine went for $41,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Mach 5 ''Speed Racer'' prototype, complete with a hydraulic
system for jumping and swinging saw-blade cutters for chopping down
obstacles, was built last year and sold during the auction to
benefit the Child Safety Network.
</P>
<P>
   ''This car is sure to bring back childhood memories for those
who watched the show as well as pique the curiosity of younger
automobile enthusiasts,'' said former publishing magnate Robert E.
Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-year-old chairman emeritus of Petersen Publishing Co. led
the drive to start the 5-year-old museum. He and his wife have
provided more than $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen paid $180,000 for the ''Speed Racer'' car and $45,000
for the 1998 Volkswagen Beetle that Mike Myers drove in ''Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana-based Kruse International is the world's largest
collector car organization. The company was bought last year by the
online auction company eBay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.kruseinternational.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
