<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's PRI Appears Ahead in Vote  </HEADLINE>
By LUIS LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   XALAPA, Mexico (AP) -- After stunning losses that cost it the
presidency and a key governorship, Mexico's long-ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party on Monday won a clear majority in
municipal elections in a core support state.
</P>
<P>
   With 96 percent of the vote counted from Sunday's elections in
Veracruz state, election officials said the PRI held onto most of
the seats in the state legislature and won 120 of the 210 city
halls, the government news agency Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
   It also won back three key mayorships held by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI toppled the leftist Democratic Revolution Party in
Minatitlan and Coatzocoalcos, two of the most important cities in
Mexico's oil industry. In the coffee and farming center of Orizaba,
the PRI defeated the National Action Party of President-elect
Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our position on the political landscape isn't for nothing,''
said the PRI's leader in Veracruz, Raul Ramos. ''It is owed to
intense work on the part of all.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Action Party of President-elect Vicente Fox won 31
municipalities, including the capital of Xalapa and the port city
of Veracruz. The party was leading a tight race in two others,
Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's largest leftist party, Democratic Revolution, won 23,
while minor parties won the remaining municipalities, Notimex
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout was low -- 40 percent, according to estimates by two
major parties. Officials blamed heavy rain and a lack of
campaigning for many of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   There was also scattered violence in the south of the state.
Three people were arrested and at least 10 opposition activists
were injured in clashes at several polling places, election
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI needed a strong showing in Veracruz to prove that it
retained strength in at least one of its strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   Recent elections have seen the party's power erode since Vicente
Fox's stunning victory July 2 that booted the PRI from the
presidency after seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the PRI lost the strongest of its strongholds --
the state of Chiapas, where an opposition coalition won the
gubernatorial elections.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI started losing its hold on Veracruz in 1997 when
opposition parties won 107 of the 210 counties. Many had speculated
opposition parties would gain more ground Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders accused the PRI of resorting to old tactics
to maintain power, and election officials admonished state
government officials for touting public works projects in the media
before the polls opened.
</P>
<P>
   ''This takes away from the transparency of the elections by
stooping so low,'' said Uriel Flores, a Democratic Revolution
representative.
</P>
<P>
   The state is governed by Miguel Aleman, a powerful, former top
executive of Mexico's Televisa TV network and son of an
ex-president whose last name recalls an era when the party ruled
almost without opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 0052 </TRAILER>
