<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buffalo teachers won't rule out job action  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Members of the Buffalo Teachers Federation
voted Monday to authorize their executive board to do ''whatever it
takes'' to secure a contract - including strike.
</P>
<P>
   The BTF, which represents about 4,000 teachers, and the Board of
Education are scheduled to meet Tuesday with a negotiator, The
Buffalo News reported. Any decision on a job action could come as
soon as Tuesday night with the action to begin Wednesday - the
first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers have been without a contract since June 1999 and
BTF President Philip Rumore said the latest offer from the Board of
Education calls for no pay increase the first year, a 1 percent
hike the next, followed by pay increases of 2 percent, 1.5 percent
and 2 percent the final year of a five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are also being asked to work an extra two days a year
with no additional pay and the Board of Education wants retirees to
accept a cut in their health benefits, Rumore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very angry group of people,'' Rumore said. ''They
feel they have been treated shabbily by the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teachers have suggested that they begin so-called
''rotating strikes,'' Rumore said. In rotating strikes, all the
teachers at randomly targeted schools would fail to report to work
on specified days.
</P>
<P>
   But under the state's Taylor Law, striking is illegal for public
employees. And for every day spent on strike, teachers would be
fined an additional day. The teachers have a strike fund of more
than $5.5 million in place.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing not to ''cave into BTF demands,'' Board of Education
President Paul Buchanan called the BTF action part of a strategy to
pressure the board.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Buchanan, an agreement may be close at hand on
back pay. That settlement would give the teachers $25 million,
although that issue is separate from the current contract
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that he assumes - and hopes - that any action the
teachers take would involve such things as informational picketing,
but not a strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''There comes a point in time when the two sides have to
negotiate,'' Mike Eagan, a special-education teacher and a member
of the executive committee said. ''This is an inappropriate way for
public officials to act. They're not negotiating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 0131 </TRAILER>
