<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Plane Crash Kills Eight  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- A pilot and seven passengers apparently
lost consciousness and their twin-propeller plane traveled hundreds
of miles across Australia on autopilot before running out of fuel
and crashing Tuesday. Authorities said all aboard were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the Beechcraft King Air 200 lost cabin
pressure minutes after taking off from Perth in western Australia,
causing those aboard to black out because of a lack of oxygen,
aviation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was similar to one in October in which two-time U.S.
Open golf champion Payne Stewart and five others died when their
Learjet drifted on autopilot for hours before running out of fuel
and crashing in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian chartered flight traveled 1,760 miles over six
hours along a fairly straight line before crashing near Mount Isa
in northwest Australia, the Australian Maritime Safety Authority
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would appear as though the airplane was on autopilot,
certainly on heading hold and it would have maintained a constant
heading until the aircraft ran out of fuel,'' said Barry Sargeant,
deputy director of the Australian Transport Safety Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Two planes took off from central Australia to track the stricken
aircraft, which was taking seven miners to the western Australian
gold town of Leonora, but both failed to establish radio contact
with the pilot, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Flying Doctors Service pilot Steve Patrick, one of those
pilots, said he was unable to detect any movement or light in the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plane was slowly descending the whole way and then it
descended into the ground,'' he told Australian Broadcasting Corp.
radio. ''There was an explosion on impact and there was a fire
straight after.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of Gwalia, one of Australia's largest gold producers,
had chartered the plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
