<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina President in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- With a vote-buying scandal brewing at home,
Argentina's embattled president left on an 11-day political trip
that is being billed as a chance to hoist the country out of its
recession.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando De la Rua arrived in Mexico on Monday, where
he was to meet with President Ernesto Zedillo and President-elect
Vicente Fox for informal talks about commercial issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has been interested for the past two years in an alliance
with Mercosur, the Latin American free trade bloc made up of
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. Bolivia and Chile are
associated members.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua will also visit Canada, China and the United States,
where he will attend the United Nations Millennium Summit and meet
with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, showing signs of emerging from a 16-month recession,
is seeking new markets for its exports, particularly in China. De
la Rua also may hope to encourage investment in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua leaves behind a federal investigation of accusations
that his administration bribed a string of senators with hundreds
of thousands of dollars to ensure passage of a labor reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Carlos Liporaci has demanded eight senators be stripped of
their congressional immunity so they can be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   It was unlikely De la Rua and Mexican officials would discuss
the case of former intelligence officer Ricardo Miguel Cavallo, who
has been implicated in Argentina's so-called ''dirty war'' against
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Cavallo, wanted by criminal judges in Spain, France and Italy
for alleged human rights abuses during the 1970s and early 1980s,
was arrested Aug. 24 in Mexico City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
