<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum To Show Film on Baja Calif.  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Swimming in the glowing blue waters of the Sea
of Cortez, Iliana Ortega watches giant sharks pass by. ''You know,
humans are much more dangerous to sharks than they are to us ...
but you must command their respect. They are always testing,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again the great gray shapes swim past on the giant
IMAX screen in the new film ''Ocean Oasis,'' which will have its
world premiere Sept. 12 at the Smithsonian's National Museum of
Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   The massive six-story tall screen pulls the viewer into the
film, featuring Mexico's 700-mile long Baja California peninsula
and the Gulf of California that it encloses.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to Baja ''is like walking 1,000 miles through sand and
finding water ... it's an oasis for the heart,'' says Ortega, a
naturalist from Mexico City who has been studying the ocean life
there for years.
</P>
<P>
   Oasis for the heart it is, and much more for wildlife adapted to
the hot, dry land and cold, nutrient-rich waters that characterize
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sights in store for the IMAX audience:
</P>
<P>
   --Male elephant seals the size of trucks battling on the beaches,
smashing their great bulk together until the loser rushes off in
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   --Terns executing an exotic mating dance before ornithologist
Enriqueta Velarde. Tango music added to the film scores a bit of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   --Giant manta rays swimming placidly in the sea, allowing Ortega
to rub their bellies.
</P>
<P>
   --A seagull tugging sharply on the wing of another gull, which
seems to cry ''ow'' with each pull.
</P>
<P>
   --A whale surfacing gently beside a boatload of tourists,
seemingly happy to have then rub its skin.
</P>
<P>
   Naturalist Exequiel Ezcurra narrates most of the 38-minute film.
He's a man who clearly loves this place and wants to share it with
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The film was made under the guidance of the San Diego Natural
History Museum, with the aim of drawing attention to the Baja
region and raising money for its conservation needs,
producer-director Soames Summerhays said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government has been quite progressive in protecting
the area, Summerhays said in an interview, but funds are not always
available.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Mexicans were full partners in making the film, said
Michael W. Hager, director of the San Diego museum.
</P>
<P>
   During development of the project Hager called in experts in
large-format film to discuss how best to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ''They all said, find people doing research in the area and let
the public see the place through their eyes, so that's what we
did,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The large-format IMAX screens provide stunning reality to
moviegoers, but making these films comes with its own set of
problems -- such as a noisy 350-pound camera.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like steering a Volkswagen underwater, to get those
close-up, intimate shots. We made the decision early on we wanted
it eye to eye, for people to see it as if they were there,'' said
Hager.
</P>
<P>
   Added Summerhays: ''It took a lot of patience, accommodating the
animals to what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some little sergeant major fish along the reefs were very
territorial and became belligerent, pecking at the camera lens, he
said, but generally the filmmakers were tolerated well.
</P>
<P>
   Even the massive elephant seals ignored them on the beach --
though one making a fast retreat from a losing battle ran into the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   While Summerhays wants to raise consciousness of the Baja area
and its ecosystem, the film doesn't have a blatant conservation
message, simply letting the beauty of nature speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   After premiering in Washington -- where it will run for at least
six months -- the film will also have openings in Mexico City and
Baja. It will open at the San Diego museum next April when that
facility launches its own IMAX theater.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Museum of Natural History: http://www.nmnh.si.edu
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Natural History Museum: http://www.sdnhm.org
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Oasis site: http://www.oceanoasis.org
</P>
</TEXT>
