<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Premier Predicts Long Battle  </HEADLINE>
By CIARAN GILES
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spain's prime minister says the Basque
terrorist group ETA and its supporters are ''Nazis'' and that
prospects are slim for peace -- or even negotiations -- with the
group blamed for an upsurge of separatist killings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a long road,'' Jose Maria Aznar said in an
interview Monday with The Associated Press. ''We're faced with
terrorism, pure and simple. And in the European Union and modern
democracies of this century there can be no room for terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Aznar spoke upon returning to his Moncloa Palace residence in
Madrid after nearly a month in his seaside home in eastern Spain --
a holiday interrupted by funerals for five of the eight people
killed this summer in car bombs and shootings blamed on ETA.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent victim was Manuel Indiano, a town councilor for
Aznar's Popular Party gunned down in his candy shop. The killing
brought to 10 the number of Popular Party councilors whose deaths
are blamed on ETA. Aznar embraced Indiano's sobbing relatives
during the burial last Wednesday in the Basque town of Zumarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had better Augusts,'' Aznar said bitterly Monday. ''I
hope to have better ones in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiano's death was the 12th since ETA ended a 14-month
unilateral cease-fire in December and unleashed one of its most
brutal offensives ever in what many see as a desperate attempt to
force the government into negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ETA, a Basque-language acronym for Basque Homeland and Freedom,
demands the right to self determination for Spain's three Basque
provinces in the north. It envisions an independent state that
would also incorporate Basque regions in southwestern France.
</P>
<P>
   ETA was particularly active toward the end of the dictatorship
of Gen. Francisco Franco and the first few years of Spain's
transition to democracy following his death in 1975. The violence
subsided slightly under the socialist government that ended in 1996
with Aznar's first election as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Basques have maintained a separate cultural
identity and language. For some, ETA's fight is a legitimate battle
for sovereignty. But the majority of Spaniards oppose their goals,
pointing out that under Spain's democratic constitution, the
Basques enjoy more autonomy than any other region in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Terrorism is just another expression of tyranny,'' Aznar said.
''They are Nazis, those people who support terrorism in the Basque
Country.''
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire was ETA's longest in its 32-year-campaign that
has been blamed for 800 deaths. A single round of negotiations
failed to get either side to budge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will never accept Spanish democracy or liberties in Spain
being sacrificed on the altar of some negotiations that might prove
justification for the terrorists,'' said Aznar, a survivor of a car
bomb attack in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does the possibility of negotiation exist?'' he asked. ''I
rule it out from the start. The day democracy yields to terrorism
it will be dealing a killing stab not just to this democracy but to
others too.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence brought an end to any political honeymoon for Aznar
after winning a second term in office with a landslide victory in
the March elections. At the time he was hailed at home and abroad
as representing a new and dynamic Spain whose centrist policies
were fueling a thriving economy.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, the country's Basque conflict is beginning to
seriously tarnish Spain's image and undermine Spanish morale.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar rules out any fresh initiatives and insists the government
will persist in maintaining law and order, boosting police
efficiency and seeking greater international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Perseverance is what brings victory,'' he said ''Nobody has a
magic wand for a solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
