<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 05:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Gives Opinion on Lee Ruling  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The twisting case of a Los Alamos
scientist accused of mishandling nuclear secrets has ensnared two
new and surprising disputants -- federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   Wen Ho Lee, whose bail-release order was signed by U.S. District
Judge James Parker, had his Labor Day weekend homecoming plans
canceled after the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals superseded
Parker's order Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers planned to make another run Tuesday at the appeals
court, hoping to spring their client from the Santa Fe County jail,
where he has been kept since December in solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Parker had issued a memorandum explaining his bail decision,
saying the government failed to present convincing arguments for
keeping Lee jailed pending trial, scheduled for Nov. 6. Bail was
set at $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer clear, Parker said, that the materials Lee is
accused of mishandling were the ''crown jewels'' of U.S. nuclear
technology, as the government contended.
</P>
<P>
   The government later filed a formal petition for a stay with the
10th Circuit -- after that court had already issued a stay, without
hearing from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court's decision even surprised Parker, who said
he had been about to refuse the prosecution's bid for a stay when
he was handed the 10th Circuit order. The defense, which had
arguments prepared, was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your honor, this isn't the way the judicial system is supposed
to work. It just isn't,'' defense attorney John Cline told Parker
on Friday. Cline had notified the prosecution Thursday of its
obligation to give him advance notice of any petition for a stay.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney George Stamboulidis, who initially filed
his appeal with Parker's court, said he had been unaware that the
Justice Department had already contacted the appeals court -- or
that the appeals court had acted -- until Parker read the stay order
from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Cline said Monday the defense would file a response to that
petition Tuesday. He said he received no response during the
weekend from the Circuit Court to Lee's Friday petition for
reconsideration of the stay.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Taiwan-born scientist, a naturalized U.S.
citizen, allegedly downloaded restricted data about nuclear weapons
to unsecure computers and tapes at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of all 59 counts, Lee could face life in prison.
Supporters say Lee is being singled out because of his race, which
prosecutors deny.
</P>
<P>
   Parker had set strict conditions on Lee's release, including
electronic monitoring, video surveillance, a phone tap,
restrictions on travel and severe limits on the number of people
with whom Lee could communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Lee: http://www.wenholee.org
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory: http://www.lanl.gov/worldview
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
