<HEADLINE> Series of Quakes Jolt Western India  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Two moderate earthquakes and seven
aftershocks jolted parts of the western Indian state of Maharashtra
early Tuesday, causing walls to crack in a mosque and in houses of
several villages, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No casualties were immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   The first quake of 5.0 magnitude hit the city of Warna, 135
miles southeast of Bombay, at 6:03 a.m., the Meteorological
Department said. The second, measuring 3.5 in intensity, hit at
6:39 a.m. southeast of Warna.
</P>
<P>
   ''The earth was shaking and people ran out of their houses,''
said Varsha Shegde in Kohlapur, a city in southern Maharashtra.
''It lasted about half a minute or so. Then it was all normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some houses in the city were cracked, said state government
spokesman Prahlad Jadhav.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are quite used to tremors. This area is prone to them,''
said Shegde. ''But this was stronger than the previous one,'' a 3.5
magnitude quake on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Shock waves from the earthquake were felt in Bombay, India's
financial hub and the capital of Maharashtra, the Press Trust of
India said, but there were no immediate reports of damage.
</P>
<P>
   The temblors were located within a seven-mile radius of the
Tandoli and Koyana dams, but there were no reports of damage, the
United News of India said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
