<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 07:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amnesty Reports on Palestinians  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority routinely
arrests those who oppose its policies, creating an atmosphere
hostile to free expression, Amnesty International said in a report
published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Describing an ''established pattern'' in a 15-page report, the
London-based human rights watchdog said: ''The Palestinian
Authority has detained dozens of human rights defenders,
journalists, religious figures, writers, government officials,
trade unionists and academics solely for exercising their
legitimate rights to freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty said it had chronicled 13 cases of ''prisoners of
conscience'' in 2000 so far. Many are detained without charges for
weeks or even months, it said; some reported being tortured.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Attorney General Khaled Qidreh said he did not
receive a copy of the report, so he could not comment. Amnesty
officials said the report was sent to Qidreh's office and other
officials a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, Amnesty said the PA has not responded to its
concerns. On the few occasions it has, it has justified detentions
on the grounds of ''security,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty suggested that the arrests create an atmosphere of
intimidation. ''Perceived criticism of PA officials and
institutions, in particular the president and members of the
various Palestinian security forces, is a dangerous area,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bassam Eid, the director of the Palestine Human Rights
Information Campaign, said the report appeared accurate -- and he
said conditions were not about to change.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, it's going to continue, because human rights
are not on the Palestinian Authority agenda,'' said Eid, himself
the target of arrests in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists told Amnesty investigators that they now practice
self-censorship because they fear retribution. Others targeted
included clerics who had preached against regime policies, and
union activists who led strikes. The only improvement the report
noted was that human rights workers were no longer targeted --
apparently following heavy international criticism prompted by a
number of arrests in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent among Amnesty's case histories were the 20 influential
residents who signed a November 1999 petition that held Arafat
directly responsible for corruption in the authority.
</P>
<P>
   That broke a taboo against directly criticizing Arafat. Some
were jailed and others were placed under house arrest. Arafat
threatened to lift the legislative immunity of lawmakers who signed
the petition.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Sattar Qassem, a 56-year-old political science professor
who had circulated the petition, was held for the longest period --
from Feb. 18 this year until July 28. The Palestinian High Court
ordered his immediate release on July 6, but it was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Such disregard for other branches of government was typical, the
report suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Arafat has failed to ratify a 1996 law passed by the
Palestinian Legislative Council that would guarantee freedom of
expression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 0756 </TRAILER>
