<HEADLINE> Vietnam-American Sentenced to Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- A Vietnamese-American lawyer has been
sentenced to death here for killing his wife, a court official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Dinh Xung, 60, of Los Angeles, received the sentence in a
one-day trial last Thursday in Ho Chi Minh City, the official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. Xung has 15 days to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear why the sentence was not reported
for five days.
</P>
<P>
   Xung told the court that he stabbed his wife, Le Thi Thanh Xuan,
48, in a Ho Chi Minh City hotel in June 1999 because he believed
she had had extramarital affairs after they came to Vietnam to meet
her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel workers found Xuan's body in the room. She had been
stabbed 29 times. Xung was arrested in Vung Tau, 80 miles southeast
of Ho Chi Minh City, where he had fled on a hydrofoil.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Xung moved to the United States 20 years ago and
divorced his first wife. Xuan, whom he married in 1997, was a widow
with two children.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently eight other Americans in Vietnamese prisons,
according to the U.S. Embassy. Four more Americans were recently
released as part of a mass amnesty marking Vietnam's National Day
Sept 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
