<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechens Face Winter in Exile  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Some 170,000 Chechen refugees are facing a second
winter in exile in neighboring Ingushetia, and increasing numbers
risk eviction from their temporary homes, the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''No significant numbers of people have gone back to Chechnya
because of the obvious instability there,'' UNHCR spokesman Kris
Janowski said. The agency is ''digging in and preparing for the
winter,'' building a tent city for 12,000 people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are signals that some of the Chechens might
have outstayed their welcome in Ingushetia, Janowski said. Over the
past week, he said, 26 people were evicted by host families or from
occupied premises, while another 216 face ''immediate threat'' of
eviction.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR is negotiating with hosts or finding alternative
accommodation in tents, Janowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops returned to Chechnya last fall to suppress the
republic's separatist government after being driven out at the end
of a 1994-96 war. The Russian military controls large areas of
Chechnya but appears to be far from defeating the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The small neighboring Russian republic of Ingushetia took in
most of the estimated 250,000 refugees who fled Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The influx strained the area's limited resources. Aid convoys
will continue through the winter ''since it's unlikely that any
significant number of people will go back,'' while a project is
under way to repair the republic's crumbling water system, Janowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Interfax news agency reported that Russian
forces have lost 23 military helicopters in the war in Chechnya
since fighting began about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The report, citing unidentified Defense Ministry officials,
marked the first time the military gave a total figure for the
number of helicopters destroyed in the war, although some
individual losses have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of 23 helicopters would be a major drain for the
cash-strapped military, which rarely receives new weapons. Military
spokesman in Moscow declined to comment on the Interfax report.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Russian officials decided this week to
move the republic's pro-Russian administration to Grozny by Oct. 15
from its temporary base in Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city
18 miles to the east, Izvestia newspaper reported Tuesday. Grozny
is the republic's traditional capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
