<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Dissident Asks Clinton's Help  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- In a message purportedly smuggled from prison,
one of China's most prominent political prisoners asked President
Clinton to urge China's president at a U.N. summit this week to
enact democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Wang Youcai appealed to Clinton to impress upon
President Jiang Zemin that he and the Communist Party he heads have
the power to bring about orderly political reform in China. The
presidents are to meet Friday on the sidelines of the U.N.
Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Mr. Jiang Zemin can establish democratic, constitutional
government in China during his term, he will be publicly recognized
as a great man by people in all of China and the world,'' said the
letter. If not, he will become ''an obstacle to China's melding
with the world and to its advance toward democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, if authentic, would be among the first from Wang
since he was jailed nearly two years ago for organizing the
opposition China Democracy Party. Dissident colleagues of Wang's in
New York sent the letter to news organizations Tuesday, although
its origins were unclear.
</P>
<P>
   According to dissident Shi Lei, a woman believed to be in the
Chinese police force contacted Xie Wanjun, a fellow Democracy Party
organizer who now lives in New York. She instructed Xie to change
his e-mail address because his was blocked by China's Internet
police, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours, a typed version of the letter, dated Aug. 24,
arrived in Xie's new e-mail box. Shi said Xie believed the letter's
contents were consistent with Wang's ideas and he discussed it with
Wang's wife, Hu Jiangxia.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone, Hu said the letter's tone sounded like
Wang, but he never mentioned it on July 15, her last visit to
Quzhou prison, 120 miles from their home in the eastern city of
Hangzhou. However, she, said, their visits are very supervised.
</P>
<P>
   The letter carried a supposed prescript from Wang hinting at its
passage from prison: ''If this letter to U.S. President Clinton
makes it over the wall, it shows that the opposition force of the
China Democracy Party has already gained the active support of
democratic people within the Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissidents in New York sent the letter to the White House and
the U.S. Congress, said Shi.
</P>
<P>
   Wang was a respected and effective organizer within China's
persecuted dissident community. A student leader of the 1989
democracy demonstrations in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, Wang
publicly launched the China Democracy Party in June 1998, vowing to
challenge the Communist Party's political monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Activists set up party organizations in 24 provinces and
attracted 200 members, according to New York-based Human Rights
Watch. But within six months, Wang and two other veteran organizers
were convicted of subversion. All told, at least 34 members of the
China Democracy Party have been imprisoned. Wang was sentenced to
11 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of China's impending entry to the World Trade
Organization, the letter noted that it would be impossible for
China to use its current political system and ideology to block
change.
</P>
<P>
   The letter called on Jiang to end controls on the media and stop
trying to block the Internet. He also appealed to Clinton to
maintain political, economic and cultural contacts with China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 0910 </TRAILER>
