<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 28; Nasdaq Falls 31  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower Tuesday, as investors
returned from a holiday weekend to a market with little news to
influence trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average fell 28.49 to 11,210.29.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 31.67 at 4,202.66, The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 6.77 to 1,514.00.
</P>
<P>
   With no big news to provide a clear direction for trading, the
market drifted in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed higher Friday after a day of low-volume trading as
many left for the Labor Day holiday. Unemployment and productivity
figures released Friday, while containing mixed figures, seemed to
indicate that inflationary pressures are under control.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate edged up to 4.1 percent in August and
total payrolls fell by a bigger-than-expected 105,000 during the
month, the largest drop in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the decline in total employment, which is seasonally
adjusted, came from the departure of 158,000 temporary Census
workers and the impact of striking workers at Verizon, the nation's
largest local phone company and wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 0.42 at 542.33.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.41 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.92 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.56 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.38 percent.
</P>
