<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Drops 33; Dow Gains 9  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Tuesday, as investors returned
from a holiday weekend to a market with little news to influence
trading.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 9.25 at 11,248.03.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 33.04 at 4,201.29. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 4.99 to 1,515.78.
</P>
<P>
   With no big news to provide a clear direction for trading, the
market drifted in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Niagara Mohawk Holdings rose $2 to $15.88 in early
trading after British-based National Grid Group PLC announced it
was buying it for $3 billion in cash and stock. Niagra Mohawk is
the second-largest electric and gas utility in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell $2.91 to $71.03 in early trading after a U.S. Bancorp
Piper Jaffray analyst downgraded the computer chip-maker's stock to
buy from strong buy.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues trailed decliners by a narrow margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 110.35 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 1.33 at 540.58.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.41 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.92 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.56 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.38 percent.
</P>
