<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Orders Exam on Siamese Twins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A British appeals court gave permission Tuesday
for additional scans on Siamese twins whose parents are fighting
against having them separated.
</P>
<P>
   A judge previously ruled that the twins should be separated to
give the strong one a chance at a normal life. If not separated,
the judge said both twins would die.
</P>
<P>
   The parents have objected to medical interference in what they
see as God's will.
</P>
<P>
   David Harris, an attorney representing the Official Solicitor,
told the three-judge panel in the Court of Appeal Tuesday that a
pediatric cardiologist was joining a surgeon to examine the twins
later Tuesday at St. Mary's Hospital in Manchester. They expect to
report back to the court by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the surgeon, from the Great Ormond Street Children's
Hospital medical team which has separated other twins, had said
there might be a need for further scans.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court requested a second medical opinion before
making a life-and-death decision about the fate of the
four-week-old Siamese twins.
</P>
<P>
   That request came Monday at the start of legal action by the
girls' parents to block a High Court ruling that would mean certain
death for one of their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert Johnson ruled last month that Jodie -- the stronger
of the twins -- should be separated from her sister Mary, who is
reliant on her sister's lungs and heart to survive. If they are
separated, Mary will die, medical experts said. But without the
surgery, both twins are likely to perish within three to six months
because of the extra strain on Jodie's organs. Mary and Jodie are
not the their real names, and the family has not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were born joined at the lower abdomen on Aug. 8 in
Manchester. Judith Parker, a lawyer assigned to represent the
stronger twin, said medical experts believed that she would not
face significant problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must look at it not that something is being done to Mary to
hasten the end of her life, but that something is being done to
Jodie in order to restore to her own integrity and bodily system,''
Parker told the court.
</P>
<P>
   But the parents say they do not want one of their children
''actively killed''.
</P>
<P>
   Their barrister Simon Taylor told the appeal court they had come
to the ''heartbreaking'' decision that they could not kill one of
their daughters to allow the other to survive as, in their view,
that was not God's will.
</P>
<P>
   They also feared that Jodie would face a life of suffering if
she were to survive and return home with them, where there was
concern over local attitudes to disability and no real access to
high-level care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1041 </TRAILER>
