<HEADLINE> Small Plane Crashes in Australia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- With its pilot and seven passengers
apparently unconscious, a twin-propeller plane continued to fly
across Australia on autopilot for six hours before it ran out of
fuel and crashed Tuesday, killing all eight.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe those on board blacked out from lack of
oxygen when their Beechcraft King Air 200 lost cabin pressure
shortly after taking off from Perth in western Australia, aviation
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar crash in South Dakota in October killed two-time U.S.
Open golf champion Payne Stewart and five others aboard a Learjet
that drifted on autopilot for hours before running out of fuel and
crashing.
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of Gwalia, one of Australia's largest gold producers,
had chartered the plane that crashed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other planes took off from central Australia to track the
stricken aircraft, which was taking seven miners to the western
mining town of Leonora, but both failed to establish radio contact
with the pilot, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Flying Doctors Service pilot Steve Patrick, one of those
pilots, said he was unable to detect any movement or light in the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plane was slowly descending the whole way and then it
descended into the ground,'' he told Australian Broadcasting Corp.
radio. ''There was an explosion on impact and there was a fire
straight after.''
</P>
<P>
   The chartered flight traveled 1,760 miles during six hours along
a fairly straight line before crashing near Mount Isa in northwest
Australia, the Australian Maritime Safety Authority said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would appear as though the airplane was on autopilot,
certainly on heading hold and it would have maintained a constant
heading until the aircraft ran out of fuel,'' said Barry Sargeant,
deputy director of the Australian Transport Safety Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
