<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 41; Nasdaq Falls 55  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were slightly lower Tuesday, as investors
returned from a holiday weekend to a market with little news to
influence trading.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-morning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 41.44 at 11,197.34.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 55.33 to 4,179.00. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index dropped 12.48 to 1,508.29.
</P>
<P>
   With no big news to provide a clear direction for trading, the
market drifted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it will be a very slow week,'' said Eugene Mitz, a
financial markets analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co. He said
the economy appears to be slowing, but many investors aren't sure
what that means for their portfolios. Barring any major corporate
announcement or other financial news, Mintz said it might take time
for the market to find direction.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks pretty much like people are just sitting back and
saying, 'We'll wait and see for a while before doing anything,'''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Niagara Mohawk Holdings rose $1.88 to $15.75 after
British-based National Grid Group PLC announced it was buying the
utility for $3 billion in cash and stock. Niagara Mohawk is the
second-largest electric and gas provider in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher Scientific International's shares jumped $9.06, about
41.3 percent, to $31. The company announced late Friday its $800
million plan to buy PSS World Medical Inc., another medical
products distributor, had fallen apart. The plan was not popular
with investors.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell $4.06 to $69.88 in early trading after a U.S. Bancorp
Piper Jaffray analyst downgraded the computer chip maker's stock to
''buy'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues trailed decliners by a narrow margin on the New
York Stock Exchanges, where volume came to 266.56 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 2.57 at 539.34.
</P>
