<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At The Movies: 'Nurse Betty'  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Nurse Betty'' is the year's most enjoyable -- and most
surprising -- fairy tale. Its heroine is a modern-day Don Quixote, a
romantic living out her fantasies more than even she could have
imagined. The director is Neil LaBute, who seemed cold to romance
of any kind -- much less a fairy tale -- in ''Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors''.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Zellweger stars as Betty Sizemore, a diner waitress from
Fair Oaks, Kan. She's bored with her job and not too excited by her
husband (LaBute favorite Aaron Eckhart). When two hit men (Morgan
Freeman and Chris Rock) destroy her home for good, she lives out
her version of the American Dream: Get in your car, drive West and
prepare to meet a man who doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   The intended is Dr. David Ravell (Greg Kinnear), the handsome
lead character of ''Reason to Love,'' a daytime drama Betty watches
with unnerving attention. To meet him, she has reinvented herself
as a nurse from Ravell's hospital, an old fiancee back in town to
reclaim her lost love. It's her great fortune, and ours, that the
makers of ''A Reason to Love'' mistake her for a particularly
dedicated method actress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nurse Betty'' is a model for how the fairy tale should work;
you know it couldn't happen in real life, but you believe it could
happen in this movie. Every strange plot turn is justified by the
writing -- and by the actors. When performers refer to their work as
''magic time,'' they're thinking of movies like this.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute didn't write the script; a good thing since Betty would
have never made it out of Kansas. Instead, honors go to John C.
Richards and James Flamberg. Their screenplay is funny,
tough-minded, graceful. It has all the best qualities of LaBute's
work and a generous spirit the director never summoned on his own.
For the first time in his films, a woman isn't punished for having
a good heart.
</P>
<P>
   The script works even better when these performers read the
lines. Zellweger's husky-squeaky voice is the closest thing we have
to Jean Arthur these days. She's an ideal comic actress, glamorous
but down-to-earth, believable as the eye in the storm and the storm
itself. In ''Jerry Maguire'' and ''Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' Zellweger
played the sanest person in the movie; the ultimate good sport. In
''Nurse Betty,'' she's quite the opposite, single-minded to the
point of madness.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman's part is smaller, but just as satisfying. He's a gifted
actor often typecast in ''dignified'' roles. This time, as an aging
crook, he plays a far richer character: tired, compromised, but
still yearning. He has dignity, too, but it's not imposed by the
filmmakers; it comes from within.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood hasn't looked kindly upon the obsessed fan. The
classic image is Kathy Bates in ''Misery'' -- lonely, lethal and,
the biggest sin in show business, unattractive. But ''Nurse Betty''
taps a wand on the head of its title character and invites her to
the dance. LaBute, a cynic on holiday, was clearly taken by her
story. None of us should feel ashamed of being charmed as well.
</P>
<P>
   A Gramercy Pictures release, ''Nurse Betty'' was produced by
Gail Mutrux and Steve Golin. The running time is 112 minutes and
the rating is ''R,'' with violence and adult situations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
