<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At The Movies: 'The Way of the Gun'  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTY LEMIRE
For The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you learn early on in ''The Way of the Gun'' that the main
characters go by the names ''Parker'' and ''Longbaugh,'' you know
serious trouble will find them in the end, probably someplace bleak
and desolate.
</P>
<P>
   Film buffs will recognize that Parker and Longbaugh were the
real names of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid. That's a perfect
reference for ''The Way of the Gun,'' a Western thriller with a
contemporary black spin.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher McQuarrie, who won a best screenplay Oscar for
1995's ''The Usual Suspects,'' directs for the first time and
writes the script. Too bad he doesn't know when to cut himself off.
The story and dialogue are often clever, but McQuarrie drags out
the ending with not one, not two, but three big gun battles, each
more generic and tedious than the last.
</P>
<P>
   The 90 minutes leading up to those shootouts are creative and
full of surprises, though. Every character in this thing is dirty,
and no one is what he or she seems.
</P>
<P>
   Parker (Ryan Phillippe) and Longbaugh (Benicio del Toro) are
career criminals who simply have chosen not to function in normal
society. ''A plan is just a list of things that don't happen,''
Parker philosophizes, instead choosing to live day-to-day with his
buddy through sheer survival.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing they're broke, the two kidnap Robin (Juliette Lewis),
the surrogate mother of a wealthy Southwestern couple who is to
receive $1 million when her child is born. They also force her
physician (Dylan Kussman) to come along to deliver the baby.
</P>
<P>
   But as the motley group makes its way to Mexico, several twists
and turns arise involving family ties, double-crosses and hidden
agendas. A lot of them are way too coincidental to be believable,
but for the most part, McQuarrie's writing is so enthralling, he
makes it easy to go along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Strong performances from an all-star ensemble cast also keep the
movie humming until nearly the end. James Caan is excellent, gets
the best lines and steals most every scene he's in as a moneybag
man for the wealthy father-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe has a breakout performance as Parker. After seeing him
play pretty boys in ''54'' and ''Cruel Intentions,'' it's great to
watch him pull off the bad guy routine with finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Katt and Taye Diggs have some darkly funny moments as
slick, well-dressed bodyguards assigned to protect Robin, but who
get tangled up in far more violence than they anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the setting, the production design also gives ''The Way
of the Gun'' a retro Western feel. McQuarrie and director of
photography Dick Pope chose to wash out the scenes in gritty grays
and browns. So even when the plot falls apart, the movie still
looks good.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Way of the Gun,'' an Artisan Entertainment release, is
rated R for language, strong violence-gore and some sexuality.
Running time: 119 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for
</P>
<P>
   children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
