<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Korean Cancels U.N. Trip  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- North Korea's No. 2 leader called off
a trip to the U.N. Millennium Summit on Tuesday after his
delegation was allegedly ordered to undergo a strip search during a
security check as they transferred to an American Airlines flight
in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Nam, head of the communist country's parliament, was to
have met in New York with South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, just
two months after his historic summit meeting in Pyongyang with
North Korea's paramount leader.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Yong Nam would have been the highest-ranking North Korean
official to attend a U.N. meeting since both Koreas joined the
world body in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation members claimed the search Monday was ordered by
U.S. security officials, and North Korea's vice foreign minister,
Choe Su Hon, told reporters at a hastily arranged news conference
at Frankfurt airport that North Korea has demanded an apology from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a rude and provocative act,'' Choe said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines issued a statement Tuesday apologizing for the
search, but denied that the diplomats were asked to strip. No U.S.
government agencies participated in the search, American Airlines
spokesman John Hotard said from Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''This involved a 'pat down' and removal of only an outer
garment, such as a suit jacket, and their shoes,'' the airline said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are sorry for the inconvenience caused Monday to the North
Korean diplomatic delegation,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the State Department said, ''It appears that the
procedures at the airport caused an unfortunate situation that we
deeply regret.'' An official said the department will have more to
say when additional information about the situation is received.
</P>
<P>
   Choe said the search was ordered as the delegation members were
transferring to an American Airlines flight in Frankfurt, where
they arrived Monday after a stopover in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''U.S. security officials turned up, opened suitcases and
handbags of each member of the presidential entourage, forced them
to take off their clothes and shoes and thoroughly searched each
and every sensitive part of the body,'' Choe said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the incident showed ''one aspect of the insidious and
cunning double-faced stratagem of the United States,'' which he
called the ''paragon of a rogue state.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire North Korean delegation will fly back to North Korea
later Tuesday, Choe said.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean President Kim Dae-jung left Tuesday for the
Millennium Summit, where he is to discuss positive developments on
the divided Korean peninsula with world leaders and had also been
expected to meet the North Korean deputy leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a chance for another meeting, but right now
the chance is lost,'' Choe said. ''I think this matter has nothing
to do with North-South Korean relations, which are improving quite
favorably at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Dae-jung and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il agreed to
promote reconciliation and reunification during the June summit,
the first since the 1945 division of the peninsula.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
