<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Next Missile Defense Test in Jan.  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon probably will postpone the next
test of its national missile defense by a month or two so that
officials can more fully analyze the last test's failure, officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The expected delay, to January, is not directly linked to
President Clinton's decision last week to abandon a 2005 target
date for deploying a national missile defense, Air Force Lt. Col.
Rick Lehner said. He is spokesman for the Ballistic Missile Defense
Organization, the Pentagon office in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was not sufficiently confident of the technical
feasibility of a national missile defense to commit the United
States to deploying the weapon system now, but he ordered the
Pentagon to ''continue a robust program of development and
testing.'' His decision effectively removed 2005 as a target date
for deploying a missile defense, although Clinton said he believed
it was still possible by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The key to determining the feasibility of missile defense is a
series of flight tests of the missile interceptor -- a booster
rocket and a ''kill vehicle'' it carries into space to collide with
an incoming warhead.
</P>
<P>
   Each flight test costs about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The last two tests, in January and July, were unsuccessful. The
Pentagon was planning another try in October or November, although
shortly after the July failure Defense Secretary William Cohen told
Congress that it might slip to December.
</P>
<P>
   No firm date has yet been set, Lehner said, but ''more than
likely'' the next flight test will be in January. He said the
missile range on Kwajalein Atoll in the central Pacific is closed
much of December. Officials do not expect to finish analyzing the
reasons for the July test failure until October, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision means the Pentagon will not award contracts
this year for initial construction work on a new missile-tracking
radar in the Aleutians. That would have put the United States on a
path to missile defense deployment in the face of stern opposition
from Russia and China and doubts among U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from deferring work on the radar, Clinton's decision
had little immediate impact on the technical work under way or on
the enthusiasm of those involved in the project, Lehner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no real sense of disappointment,'' Lehner said.
''This was the president's decision. We'll keep pressing forward
with the test program.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon missile defense office:
http://www.acq.osd.mil/bmdo/bmdolink/html/
</P>
</TEXT>
