<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Speaker's top spokeswoman to leave at end of year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver's top
spokeswoman and strategist said Tuesday she is stepping down at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lynch said spending more time with her family after
seven years in the high-pressure job with Silver is one of her main
priorities. She has children ages 9 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time, it's just time,'' Lynch said. ''It has been a
phenomenal seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, 42, has been in and out of government since first taking
a job with former Democratic state Sen. Howard Nolan of Albany in
1978. She also worked for the Democratic minority in the state
Senate and Democratic U.S. Reps. Nita Lowey and Nydia Velazquez.
</P>
<P>
   She makes $110,000 a year in the Assembly, where she heads a
large public relations staff for majority Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said she would seek to become a public relations
consultant and lobbyist in state and New York City politics.
</P>
<P>
   She said she first told Silver that this would probably be her
last year in Albany before the 2000 legislative session, which
turned out to be Silver's most turbulent year as speaker. In May,
Democratic Majority Leader Michael Bragman openly challenged Silver
for the speaker's post - a challenge Silver fought down after days
of feverish lobbying among Democratic members.
</P>
<P>
   A major complaint of the dissidents was that Silver was isolated
from rank-and-filers by staffers such as Lynch, who emerged as the
speaker's most influential aide when former counsel Fred Jacobs
left in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Silver did appear to adopt a more open and member-friendly
attitude toward Democratic assemblymen following the coup attempt.
If he wins re-election to the Assembly in November as expected,
Silver must still be re-elected as speaker by his colleagues to
retain his top leadership position for two more years.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the past few years, the speaker and Republican Gov.
George Pataki showed an increasing willingness to work together on
major legislation. Though the Pataki and Silver camps were still
often antagonistic and always wary of each other, they did
compromise on a new state health care financing system in 1999 and
on a host of bills in 2000 which would have prompted political
sparring in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch insisted that her impending departure has nothing to with
Silver's fight to remain speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''If anything, if it were not for the coup I would have
announced earlier,'' she said. ''Between now and the end of the
year my only priority is to re-elect the speaker as speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch lives in Chappaqua, Westchester County, not far from the
new home of President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Her impending departure was first reported in Tuesday's New York
Post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1438 </TRAILER>
