<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect in Shelton woman's death blamed killing on drug dealers  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The man charged with murder in the 1998
death of a Shelton woman claims she was killed by drug dealers who
were after him because of an old debt, the arrest warrant shows.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregory McArthur could not identify for police the men who
allegedly attacked him before going after Annmarie Cusano, an
escort he had hired for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses told police they helped McArthur home after
finding him walking in the north end of Hartford that night with
stab wounds to the back and leg. But they say McArthur never
mentioned that a woman had been attacked with him.
</P>
<P>
   According to the warrant, police believe McArthur killed Cusano,
the mother of teen-age twin daughters, during a robbery the night
of Jan. 3, 1998, and was injured in the attack. A few hours later,
at a time when McArthur claimed to have already left the state, he
''rented'' Cusano's car to an acquaintance in exchange for crack
cocaine, police said.
</P>
<P>
   McArthur, the last person seen with Cusano, on Saturday led
police to her remains in a wooded area of Suffield. He was
arraigned in Hartford Superior Court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities will not say whether McArthur changed his story and
confessed, or how and why he led police to the body. McArthur, a
suspect since the beginning, had refused to cooperate with police
until he agreed last month to return to Connecticut from a
Massachusetts jail where he is serving up to 15 years on unrelated
theft charges.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant for his arrest in connection with Cusano's death was
issued in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Chief State's Attorney John Bailey said Tuesday that McArthur
had not been offered a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. McArthur voluntarily gave the location and the charges
have not been reduced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McArthur, 39, is charged with murder, felony murder and robbery.
He is scheduled to return to court Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expected to feel more hate, rage and anger,'' John Peters
said after getting his first glimpse of the man accused of killing
his sister. ''It's an emptiness. I really don't know what to
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, who sat quietly in the courtroom with Cusano's
daughters, said McArthur's arrest brings them closer to closure.
</P>
<P>
   It has also spurred fresh reports about Cusano's part-time work
for an escort service.
</P>
<P>
   Cusano, 42, supplemented her secretarial job at a Milford firm
by working as an escort for Gabriel Gladstone, a 71-year-old
Roxbury man serving 20 years in prison for running an extensive
prostitution ring, the arrest warrant shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone told police that Cusano had gone to McArthur's
Hartford boarding house the night of Jan. 2, 1998, but called her
employer just after midnight Jan. 3 and said she was ending the
date.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses reported seeing McArthur, suffering stab wounds,
between 2 a.m. and 3 a.m. on Jan. 3. The residents offered aid to
McArthur, who said he had been robbed but refused to call the
police because he had outstanding warrants against him.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the area where McArthur was found injured is not far
from Keney Park, where he had been accused three times of trying to
rob women at knifepoint. McArthur has been convicted 22 times, 12
times on felony charges.
</P>
<P>
   Between 2 a.m. and 4 a.m. on Jan. 3, McArthur allegedly rented
Cusano's car to an acquaintance in exchange for drugs. The
acquaintance contacted police when he learned of Cusano's
disappearance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1504 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
