<HEADLINE> Putin Practices Judo in Japan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin took time out Tuesday
from political talks in Japan to practice judo -- accepting flowers
from a 10-year-old Japanese girl who tossed him to the mat.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a black belt in the sport, visited a session for athletes
heading for the Sydney Olympics at the Kodokan Sports Palace with
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I am on a judo mat, I feel at home, not on a visit. When
I am with other people practicing judo, I feel as though I am with
close relatives,'' Putin said in remarks carried on Russian
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling, the trim, 47-year-old Putin did a few traditional
stretches and then rumbled with one of the athletes. He then faced
the 10-year-old, who threw him to the floor to loud applause.
</P>
<P>
   Putin left later Tuesday for the Millennium Summit at the United
Nations after two days of talks with Mori that failed to resolve a
prickly territorial dispute over the Kuril Islands, seized by the
Soviet Union at the end of World War II.
</P>
