<HEADLINE> Woman charged with stealing from dead granddaughter's benefit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - A woman is accused of stealing money
from a fund-raising event for her dying granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect's attorney, Ronald R. Benjamin, called the charge
bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson City police on Monday charged Karen J. Horton, 53, of
Union, with fourth-degree grand larceny. Horton was released
following arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   The charge stems from an Aug. 12 benefit for 5-year-old Felicia
Miller, who had terminal leukemia, said Detective Mark Wallikas.
The girl has since died. About $1,600 was raised at the event,
Wallikas said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles Club of Johnson City, where the benefit took place,
gave the check to Horton, an Eagles Club member. But instead of
sending all the money to her daughter, Samantha Spencer who is
Felicia's mother, Horton pocketed $1,400 of it, Wallikas said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallikas said Johnson City police began an investigation last
week after receiving a complaint from Spencer in Ocean Isle Beach,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   However, Horton told police she held the money because she was
going to take care of bills and because her daughter owed her, and
her husband, $800.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin called Horton's arrest ''outrageous.'' The $1,400 went
to pay medical and other bills for the dead girl, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin also said police should never have filed the charge
because Horton held on to most of the money with the permission of
the Eagles Club's board of directors. The board decided Spencer was
not responsible enough to handle the money herself.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Briggs, vice president of the Eagles Club, confirmed that
the board gave Horton responsibility for the money.
</P>
<P>
   ''All these charges are bogus,'' Briggs agreed. He said Horton
had ''100-percent backing'' of the Eagles Club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
