<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court upholds Spitzer in Internet child porn investigation  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's highest court Tuesday upheld the
right of the state attorney general's office to seize an Internet
provider's records and make its employees testify before a grand
jury in an Internet pornography investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the Court of Appeals upheld lower court rulings
in the case against BuffNet of West Seneca. Prosecutors in Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer's office are seeking the records as part of
the investigation which began with an inquiry into ''Pedo
University,'' a virtual ''college'' which prosecutors allege was
formed for the exchange of pornographic photographs of preteen
children.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen people have been arrested in the United
States, Canada, New Zealand and Sweden as part of the pornography
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   BuffNet is one of several Internet providers that prosecutors
are looking into. BuffNet and employees of the Internet service
provider, which operates under the corporate name Marketing and
Advertising Services Center Corp., have not been accused of any
wrongdoing in the case in Erie County Court.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling upholds a decision by the Appellate Division of
state Supreme Court in Rochester. Those judges ruled in May that
the attorney general has ''broad investigative and prosecutorial
powers'' to look into child pornography on the Internet when cases
are referred to his office by the state police.
</P>
<P>
   BuffNet's lawyer had argued that the attorney general's power is
limited and that to allow him access to BuffNet corporate records
and employees' testimony would give him virtually unfettered
prosecutorial power in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Robin A. Forshaw, an assistant state attorney general, said the
case represents the first time that a ''protocol'' the attorney
general's office has worked out with the state police for such
referrals and prosecutions had been challenged in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something that has been happening for a while,'' she
said. ''We don't anticipate that this is going to open the
floodgates in getting us involved in all kinds of criminal
prosecutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer spokesman Darren Dopp said the prosecution of child
pornography is nothing new, but when the illegal materials are
transmitted over the Internet authorities need new methods to
combat it.
</P>
<P>
   BuffNet's lawyer was not immediately available for comment. When
the company lost in May at the appellate division, company
executive Michael Hassett said BuffNet was only an unwilling
conduit for the transmission of pornographic materials. It would be
impossible to screen the traffic over the thousands of newsgroups
operating over BuffNet's service to weed out criminal activities,
Hassett said.
</P>
<P>
   In other rulings Tuesday by the Court of Appeals:
</P>
<P>
   -The judges agreed to decide a ''certified question'' for a
federal appeals court. The court will give its opinion on whether a
county can lay off partial liability on an inmate in its jail who
beat another inmate he had accused of informing on him.
</P>
<P>
   The injured inmate said there was a notation in his file which
told guards at the Nassau County Jail not to place him in a
situation where he could be accosted by the other inmate, who ended
up beating him severely with a broom handle. The county, hit with
an $800,000 judgment, is trying to make the attacking inmate also
liable.
</P>
<P>
   -The court refused to hear an appeal of a case absolving New
York City's board of education of responsibility for the beating a
student received on a city subway at the hands of some schoolmates.
The student had tried to contend that since the dispute originated
in school, the subway was essentially an extension of school
grounds and the board of education can be held liable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1548 </TRAILER>
