<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lucas Filming Star Wars: Episode II  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0432-----
r e *1402AP-Italy-Star-Wars     09-05 0429
*1402 AP-Italy-Star-Wars,0429   
Lucas Filming Star Wars: Episode II
AP Photo ROM105
By ALESSANDRA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASERTA, Italy (AP) -- With its marble-encrusted walls and its
frescoed rooms, the sumptuous Royal Palace was designed to be home
for the Spanish kings of Naples in the 18th century. On Tuesday, it
was occupied by a queen ---- along with Jedi Knights and the numerous
otherworldly creatures imagined by ''Star Wars'' director George
Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   The American director is in Caserta, 18 miles north of Naples,
for a two-day shoot of ''Star Wars: Episode II,'' the fifth movie
of the saga that started in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fun to be directing again,'' Lucas said at a news
conference in the court theater inside the palace, which will serve
as a backdrop for Queen Amidala's planet, Naboo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Episode II'' starts off about a decade after the end of ''Star
Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace.'' Anakin Skywalker, grown
into a teen-ager, learns the ways of the Force from Jedi Master
Obi-Wan Kenobi (played by Ewan McGregor) and falls in love with
Natalie Portman's character, Amidala, the future mother of Luke and
Leia.
</P>
<P>
   Their love is doomed as Anakin begins his journey toward the
Dark Side and becomes Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas says the film is a ''romantic story'' and ''basically a
fairy tale, but there's a lot of action, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the live-action scenes for ''Episode II,'' which is due
for release in 2002, will be shot using digital, high-definition
camcorders instead of film cameras. With ''Episode I,'' Lucas
pioneered digital projection in a few theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The advance of cinema into the digital world is just a normal
transition that's taking place, an addition to the tools'' we use
to make movies, Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   He likened it to the transition from frescoes to oil painting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oil painting freed the artists up to change his mind, go home
... and know that the colors they're using are going to stay
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The use of digital cameras also has been a time-saver on
numerous parts of the production. The first phase of the shooting
ended in late August in Australia; other locations for the
$150-million-movie include London and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Palace, nicknamed the ''Versailles of Naples'' for its
splendor, was completed in 1774 from plans by Italian architect
Luigi Vanvitelli. It is considered one of the greatest -- and last --
achievements of Italian Baroque architecture. Some scenes from
''The Phantom Menace'' also were filmed there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1558 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New rules could lead to more use of video in civil trials  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Videotaped testimony may soon become more
common in New Jersey courtrooms - and many attorneys are taking a
dim view of that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   They believe juries pay more attention to live witnesses and
that more videotaping could lead to increased costs.
</P>
<P>
   Videomakers, however, smell a bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   The potential windfall is courtesy of a committee of the state
Supreme Court, whose new rules making it harder for lawyers to
delay civil trials took effect Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to get lawsuits to trial more quickly. Lawyers now
get one postponement if an expert witness is unavailable, compared
with about six under the old rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a rule that's going to speed things up but at a cost,''
Teaneck lawyer Samuel L. Davis told The Star-Ledger of Newark for
Tuesday's editions. He said videotaping costs could affect the
potential for settlement in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do I risk not having (an expert), or do I invest what might be
half the value of a case (in videotape)? That's the dilemma,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Videotaped testimony has been allowed for 20 years under certain
circumstances, such as the unavailability of an expert or the
illness of a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Such testimony resembles pretrial depositions but edited to
exclude statements a judge later rules are inadmissible
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses in a civil trial are deposed beforehand, a proceeding
in which lawyers for all sides can attend and ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers routinely videotape these sessions, which provide much
of the work done by video companies such as IVP New Media of
Montclair.
</P>
<P>
   IVP president Michael R. DeCheser said the new rules will
''absolutely'' mean more business.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to add six videographers to the 12 he already uses
and purchase up to six more sets of video equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To help lawyers keep costs under control, DeCheser said Tuesday
that IVP will offer streaming video of depositions on a secure Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   That will save travel costs: If three lawyers in a firm are
working on a case, two could stay in the office instead of spending
a day or week at a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules were written by the Committee of Presiding Civil
Judges, in an effort to speed litigation and create uniformity in
the state's trial courts, which are spread among the 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unavailability of expert witnesses is one of the most common
reasons for adjourning a trial and one of the greatest impediments
to providing trial date certainty,'' the judges said in a report
explaining the reasoning for the rule on adjournments caused by
expert witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The civil case backlog at the end of July stood at 52,513, down
8 percent from 57,288 a year earlier, according to the state's
Administrative Office of the Courts. A civil case is considered
part of the backlog if it is more than a year old.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New Jersey State Courts:
http://www.judiciary.state.nj.us/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1602 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio manager thinks President Clinton may attend wife's first debate </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The campaign manager for Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Republican opponent in New York's U.S. Senate race said
Tuesday he has a ''sneaking suspicion'' President Clinton will show
up for his wife's first debate.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that possibility, a spokesman for the first lady's
campaign, Howard Wolfson, would say only that the president's
schedule ''has not yet been determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dal Col, Rep. Rick Lazio's campaign manager, also said he
expects the first lady to be a ''formidable debater'' and that the
congressman spent half of his four-day vacation in the posh
Hamptons on the east end of Long Island last week ''in full debate
prep.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're up against somebody who's going to be a formidable
debater, has had seven years on the national stage under intense
pressure and has performed,'' Dal Col added. ''So, when we have to
go up against somebody like that, I want to make sure our candidate
is well prepared and he will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and Lazio are scheduled to have their first
debate on Sept. 13 in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got a sitting president who's kind of bored. That's
been kind of obvious. He's trying to find things to do,'' said Dal
Col, who served as campaign manager for millionaire publisher Steve
Forbes' two failed attempts to win the GOP presidential nomination.
''Obviously, the Democratic nominee (for president) doesn't want
him around much ... (so) I got a sneaking suspicion he will be
there'' at his wife's debate.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col also said he expects if the president does show up, ''he
will be working 'spin alley,''' the area where reporters covering
the debate would be working.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing a close race, both Clinton and Lazio are
looking to the first debate to give them a boost. The first lady,
who has never before been a candidate or in a political debate, has
also begun debate practice sessions, according to aides.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the two have already agreed to at least three debates.
</P>
<P>
   A possible downside for the first lady to having President
Clinton show up at the first debate is that it could overshadow her
performance. That, of course, could be an upside if she turns out
to lack debating skills.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, there is some speculation, even within her own camp,
that she may want her husband on hand for moral support.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possible downside for the first lady of having
her husband attend or not, Dal Col said, ''I wouldn't want to get
into their family chemistry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
