<HEADLINE> Suspected Rebels Free Priest  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARITA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Suspected guerrilla kidnappers have
freed a Catholic priest whose niece is leading polls to become
Colombia's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Gerardo Sanin, 74, was released late Monday after six days
in captivity. He says he was abducted by members of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, the country's
largest guerrilla insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have neither admitted nor denied their responsibility
in the kidnapping, whose motive remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Sanin is the uncle of former foreign minister and presidential
candidate Noemi Sanin, an independent candidate preparing for a new
presidential run in 2002. His kidnapping prompted an outcry from
the Roman Catholic Church and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours after being freed, the white-bearded and bespectacled
Sanin celebrated an emotional Mass on Tuesday at his parish in a
working-class Bogota neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would forgive his captors, but nearly broke into
tears when recounting how he was forced to sleep on the chilly bare
earth while tied to a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Sanin said guerrillas walked him for hours down the mountains to
where they handed him over to fellow priests early Tuesday in
Zipaquira, a town 24 miles north of Bogota. He was abducted in the
same area Aug. 30 while on an errand to buy wood for repairs to his
parish.
</P>
<P>
   Sanin said he was in good health despite the difficult trek and
uncomfortable nights. He recalled being saved at one point from
tumbling into a steep ravine by rebel soldier who grabbed his arm
and prevented the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC is believed responsible for more than a fourth of the
roughly 3,000 kidnappings committed annually in this South American
country, mainly for ransom. The group concedes it kidnaps people to
finance its decades-old insurgency, though it rarely admits
responsibility in specific cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
