<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politics professor asks state to reject Senate campaign  </HEADLINE>
By RICH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A politics professor on Tuesday asked the
state Elections Enforcement Commission to declare Joseph
Lieberman's Senate campaign ''frivolous'' and order him off the
state ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the Democratic nominee for vice president, had
already announced his intention to run for re-election when Al Gore
selected him to be his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has since said he will continue both campaigns.
Although the decision has drawn sporadic criticism from both
Republicans and Democrats, officials - including Secretary of the
State Susan Bysiewicz, a Democrat, and Gov. John G. Rowland, a
Republican - have said state law allows Lieberman to conduct the
simultaneous campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But Fairfield University Professor John Orman contends in a
complaint hand-delivered to election regulators Tuesday that
Lieberman's candidacy is illegal because he would not serve in the
Senate if elected to both offices.
</P>
<P>
   Orman also contends the dual candidacies give Lieberman an
unfair advantage in fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spokesman Dan Gerstein said Tuesday ''there is nothing
frivolous about Senator Lieberman's campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the situation is unusual - the last similar
case was in Texas in 1988, when Lloyd Bentsen ran for vice
president and the Senate - Gerstein said Lieberman welcomed debate
about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Lieberman ''takes his responsibilities as a senator
and as a candidate very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The last thing in the world he would do is take the people of
Connecticut for granted,'' Gerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Orman, who has been with the Roman Catholic university since
1978, said the commission has a statutory duty to remove frivolous
candidates from the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Lieberman's two candidacies ... qualify for the label of
'frivolous' because his Connecticut senatorial campaign lacks
seriousness and it is irresponsibly self-indulgent,'' Orman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''The implicit agreement between any candidate and the
Connecticut electorate is that the candidate who runs for office
must first say, 'I promise, if elected to the office for which I
run, I will serve,''' he wrote. ''Without this implicit guarantee,
the candidacy would be a joke!''
</P>
<P>
   Orman also said Lieberman's vice presidential campaign promotes
his Senate campaign as well, even though the campaigns are funded
separately.
</P>
<P>
   ''This violates the intent of campaign finance laws and confuses
the voter,'' Orman said.
</P>
<P>
   The elections commission will decide this week whether it has
jurisdiction in the matter, said the panel's deputy director,
Albert Lenge. If so, it will hold a hearing on Orman's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its effect on presidential politics, Lieberman's Senate
race has implications for the balance of power in the Congress. If
Lieberman were elected to both jobs and resigned from the Senate,
it would fall to Rowland to appoint a replacement who would serve
until the next statewide election in 2002. Rowland has said he will
appoint a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, considered the prohibitive favorite over Republican
Philip Giordano, the mayor of Waterbury, could drop out of the
Senate race as late as Oct. 27 and still be replaced by a
Democratic Party nominee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1618 </TRAILER>
