<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Yorkers to world leaders: why all those cars?  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The world has literally converged on Manhattan.
New Yorkers can understand why more than 150 world leaders and
heads of state wanted to fly in for the United Nations Millennium
Summit, but why do they need all those cars?
</P>
<P>
   City officials spelled out the bad news last week - expect up to
175 motorcades featuring 1,300 vehicles per day during the summit
that runs Wednesday through Friday. TAKE THE SUBWAYS, the mayor
begged.
</P>
<P>
   Then the death knell was sounded when police announced this
doozy: streets will be closed willy-nilly if dignitaries need to be
moved.
</P>
<P>
   And with the VIPS staying in 34 hotels and private residences
all over Manhattan, many residents could be affected, like Tara
Oliver, who lives near the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   Her usual two-block walk to the subway turned into an
eight-block journey as she had to negotiate around blocked off
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ''How long are they in town?'' Oliver asked wearily during her
lunchbreak in downtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Long enough, Tara, for the police to come up with ''Stage 1''
and ''Stage 2'' levels of street closures. The list is specific and
vague at the same time. Specific: First Avenue will be closed to
vehicular traffic between 34th Street and 49th Street beginning
Wednesday at 6 a.m. through Friday at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Vague: You cannot stand or park on 34th, 35th, 36th, 37th, 38th,
39th, 40th, 42nd, 44th, 45th, 46th streets between the East River
and Second Avenue from Wednesday at 6 a.m. through Friday at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But parking or standing on 41st Street is OK?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's crazy, but the cops have been pretty patient, trying to
explain all the rules,'' said Bart Grishom, who lives in one of the
summit's no parking, no standing zones.
</P>
<P>
   It's crazy for a reason. Although much of the summit's business
is taking place at the U.N., there's also several receptions being
held in a variety of places. It doesn't help that President Clinton
is attending AND hosting several receptions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton and his entourage are staying at the
Waldorf-Astoria at Park Avenue and 50th Street. He and his
motorcade then must travel to the U.N. at First Avenue (the complex
runs from 42nd to 48th streets). Back and forth, back and forth.
Open streets, closed streets.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 6:30 p.m. Thursday, Clinton is holding a reception for
world leaders at the Metropolitan Museum of Art at Fifth Avenue and
82nd Street. What this means is road closures all over Manhattan's
East Side as all those motorcades converge on the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the 91 planned demonstrations near the U.N. police
will have to close streets for. They have to do to the same for the
unplanned ones as well.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a bright side to all of this. During Oliver's
meandering walk to the subway, she discovered a restaurant she'd
like to try. After all, the summit ends Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could be worse,'' she said. ''At least we have the subway.
I don't expect to see any world leaders down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
