<HEADLINE> French Genetic Food Fight Case Opens  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOIX, France (AP) -- Four advocates of traditional farming went
on trial Tuesday in this southern French city on charges of
destroying a field planted with genetically modified crops.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 activists rallied in support of the four who are
accused of tearing up a rapeseed field last year to protest
genetically modified foods that they say pose health risks.
</P>
<P>
   The rapeseed field, destroyed in June 1999, was the site of
research carried out by a center under the country's Agriculture
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Jouffret, director of the CETIOM research group, said the
field was intended merely for crop safety research and posed no
health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The controlled experiment was designed to provide information
on controversial genetically modified products, and it's
regrettable that the (field's) destruction caused us to lose
time,'' Jouffret told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The activists on trial said they were protesting ''complicity
between public research and multinational companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to genetically modified foods has been very strong in
France, where only a few such crops are authorized for planting.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four on trial, three are members of the Green Party and
the fourth is a member of a radical farm group.
</P>
</TEXT>
