<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, ASCAP, Agree on Music Order  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department and the American
Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers (ASCAP) agreed Tuesday
to modernize a 59-year-old court order to bring the licensing of
music for performances into the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   The original court order, entered in 1941 and amended several
times including in 1950, requires ASCAP to provide performance
licenses to music users upon request and to distribute the fees
from those licenses to its members.
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in New York, ASCAP grants licenses and collects
fees for the use of music written or published by its members.
ASCAP currently licenses about half of all musical performances in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The department said the revisions were the product of extensive
negotiations with ASCAP. The department's antitrust division has
been reviewing the music performance rights industry, including the
ASCAP court order and a similar decree covering Broadcast Music
Inc. (BMI). The government the review of the BMI order is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   After half a century of dramatic change in the music industry,
the government and ASCAP agreed on four modifications to improve
competition in music licensing and update procedures for settling
fee disputes. They would:
</P>
<P>
   --Expand and clarify ASCAP's obligation to offer certain types of
music users, including background music providers and Internet
companies, a genuine alternative to a blanket license;
</P>
<P>
   --Eliminate many detailed restrictions on ASCAP's relations with
its members;
</P>
<P>
   --Ensure that ASCAP members can switch to another performing
rights organization with penalty, and
</P>
<P>
   --Streamline license fee determination proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The proposed modifications should increase competition in the
licensing of music performance rights, reduce unnecessary
administrative burdens and improve music users' ability to resolve
rate disputes with ASCAP,'' said Assistant Attorney General Joel I.
Klein.
</P>
<P>
   The original court order resolved an antitrust case brought by
the division charging that ASCAP and certain of its members agreed
to restrict competition in licensing of performance rights and
discriminated against certain members in managing those rights.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed modifications were filed in U.S. District Court in
White Plains, N.Y. The government asked the court to allow 60 days
for public comment before implementing any revisions.
</P>
<P>
   The government also asked the court to consolidate into any
revised decree the provisions of a second court order, filed in
1947, that govern ASCAP's relations with foreign performance rights
organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1651 </TRAILER>
