<HEADLINE> Mayor conditionally supports casino gambling in city  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Tuesday he would
support casino gambling in the city as long as a portion of the
revenue stayed in the city and the casinos were kept free of
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always felt that if they allow casino gambling in New
York, then New York City should be a part of that, because it would
be just another way of diverting money out of the city,'' said
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the mayor supported building a gambling casino on
relatively isolated Governors Island, but his comments Tuesday were
the first time he has publicly backed such gambling ventures in
other parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made his remarks in response to a question about
developer Donald Trump's plans to team with a Native American tribe
in order to open a casino on the west side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the operation of a casino would have to be carried
out ''in a controlled and sensible and regulated way.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are two things to be careful of with casino gambling,''
said Giuliani. ''Organized crime, so you have to create a thorough,
very tough commission that keeps organized crime out ... (and)
there's the second thing, (that) the money should find its way into
the local community as well as going to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added: ''You accomplish both those purposes, then I
would be in favor of casino gambling. Donald Trump or anyone
else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
