<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Warns on Circumcision Clamps  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Doctors should examine carefully two popular
surgical clamps used for circumcising newborns, the Food and Drug
Administration warned, after it received reports that worn-out or
misassembled clamps have injured some infants.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is rare, said the FDA alert e-mailed to doctors'
groups. Since 1996, the FDA has collected 105 reports of injuries
linked to the two clamps, out of the 1.2 million circumcisions
performed annually. The injuries ranged from bleeding to urethral
damage. In four cases, the tip of the penis was amputated, which
required surgical repair or reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern was these could be ... prevented,'' FDA's David
Daly, who investigates problems with medical devices, said Tuesday.
''Even though the number isn't extensive, we feel it's important''
to warn doctors.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are two types of clamps widely used to hold the
foreskin away from the penis so doctors can cut it: the
Gomco/gomco-type and Mogen/mogen-type clamps.
</P>
<P>
   Among the FDA's recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   --Doctors should examine each clamp before each circumcision.
</P>
<P>
   --Discard any clamp that has nicks, stripped threads or misshapen
parts.
</P>
<P>
   --Be careful to reassemble clamps properly after cleaning and
ensure the original manufacturer sends the right part if a
replacement is needed. Misassembled clamps, or those reassembled
using parts from different manufacturers, have failed. Despite
visual similarities, clamp parts are not always interchangeable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1707 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio prosecutor says 'Dr. Death' to plead guilty  </HEADLINE>
By LIZ SIDOTI
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) - Former physician Michael Swango is
expected to plead guilty to federal charges Wednesday in New York
that he killed three patients at a Long Island veterans' hospital,
prosecutors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A nine count federal indictment handed down July 11 charged
Swango with three counts of murder, one count of assault, three
counts of making false statements and two counts of scheming to
defraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's admitting to what he's charged with and that's it,''
Franklin County Prosecutor Ron O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Swango's admission to making false statements will lead Franklin
County to charge him with aggravated murder in the poisoning of
Cynthia Ann McGee on Jan. 14, 1984, at Ohio State University's
hospital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The expected admission to making false statements gives
prosecutors in Ohio enough evidence to pursue the charge, O'Brien
said. The only evidence available previously was circumstantial, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse at the hospital had told investigators she witnessed
Swango taking a syringe into McGee's hospital room about an hour
before McGee's death, O'Brien said. Swango had said he was going to
draw blood but never did, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the kind of thing he has done before that followed
him wherever he went,'' O'Brien said. ''We had suspicions about all
of the deaths. What we were missing is a level of evidence. We
could not bring charges against him in the McGee case without an
admission from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Swango, a former intern at Ohio State University Hospitals, in
July had pleaded innocent in the 1993 deaths at the Veterans
Affairs Hospital in Northport.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in New York said Swango was expected in
court Wednesday. A court order prohibited them from commenting
further.
</P>
<P>
   Swango also is suspected of poisoning patients in Zimbabwe and
spent time in prison for poisoning co-workers in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   While Swango had been charged with only three murders, the
indictment alleged he was responsible for McGee's death and the
poisoning of another victim, Rena Cooper, at the OSU hospital in
February 1984. Cooper survived but was paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said charges will not be pursued in Cooper's case
because too much time has passed under Ohio law.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was accused of the New York killings July 11, just days
before he was to be released from a federal prison in Colorado on
charges that he lied about his criminal past to get his job at
Stony Brook, the medical school that ran the VA hospital where the
deaths occurred.
</P>
<P>
   He is accused of injecting the three patients with toxins. In
two of the cases, he told hospital staff the patients' families had
issued ''do not resuscitate'' orders, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth patient also died of suspected poisoning, but
prosecutors said they had evidence only for an assault charge in
that case.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was in the Colorado prison after admitting he failed to
disclose to Stony Brook officials that he had spent 30 months in
jail and lost his medical license in 1985 for poisoning six
co-workers in Quincy, Ill. No one died in that case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also suspect Swango may have poisoned patients at
hospitals in Zimbabwe, where he worked in 1994 after being fired by
Stony Brook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
