<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SmithKline, House Dispute Documents  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- SmithKline Beecham and a House committee
investigating drug prices remained at odds Tuesday over how many
documents the company will give the panel.
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee spokesman Peter Sheffield said
SmithKine had agreed to provide two of the 11 requested documents,
adding that the panel is considering ''all the legal options
available,'' including subpoenaing the remaining documents.
</P>
<P>
   The committee wants the information so it can determine if the
company is overcharging the Medicare system for Kytril, a drug that
prevents nausea in cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline spokesman Jeremy Hymsfeld declined to discuss the
negotiations but said the company has ''already produced a
significant volume of responsive documents.'' He said the company
believes the disputed documents are ''protected by attorney-client
privilege, which is at the heart of the judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee had given SmithKline, whose American headquarters
is in Philadelphia, until noon Tuesday to produce the 11 documents.
Previously, the firm had submitted several boxes of documents in
response to a May request by the panel.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline is one of seven companies the committee is
investigating after a Department of Health and Human Services
Report alleged that Medicare could have saved $447 million if drug
prices had been lower.
</P>
<P>
   HHS' Office of Inspector General concluded that the Health Care
Financing Administration pays more for 22 drugs, including Kytril,
because those companies charge higher-than-wholesale prices to
physicians being reimbursed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline announced Thursday that it would sell Kytril to Roche
AG, of Switzerland, for $1.23 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The divestiture is part of an effort to win regulatory approval
for SmithKline's pending $75 billion merger with another British
drug maker, Glaxo Wellcome PLC. That deal, approved by shareholders
of each company, is scheduled to close on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome markets Zofran for chemotherapy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
