<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Grid buys Niagara Mohawk in $3 billion deal  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - National Grid Group, the world's largest
independent electric transmission company, will pay more than $3
billion in cash and stock to acquire Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The power company that serves 1.55 million electricity customers
in New York state would eventually merge with another electric
system that National Grid owns and operates in three New England
states.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting company will be the ninth largest utility in the
United States with more than 3.3 million customers over
29,000-square miles.
</P>
<P>
   For Niagara Mohawk customers, there will be few visible
differences, except for possibly lower rates, said William E.
Davis, chairman and chief executive of Niagara Mohawk.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will really be very little change. Customers will call
the same numbers. They will get the same call center. The call
center will deploy the same crews in the same trucks,'' Davis said.
He will become chairman of National Grid USA and will join National
Grid's board as an executive director for two years after the
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the longer term, for the average person, we should see the
opportunity to create efficiencies and synergies that will keep
reducing our cost structure ... and lead to more stable and reduced
prices,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk will continue to operate under its own name and
keep its headquarters in Syracuse, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This transaction is in the best interests of our shareholders
and will yield significant benefits for our customers, employees
and the communities we serve,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Questioning that, the chair of the state Assembly's energy
chairman called for ''an unprecedented level of scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While this acquisition is promising a 37 percent premium on
equity for NiMo's shareholders, there is no such guarantee for the
consumer under the equation,'' said Democratic Assemblyman Paul
Tonko, of Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Tonko said the proposal failed to address consumer investment in
NiMo infrastructure, intentions for NiMo's natural gas division,
the effect on NiMo's work force and what the deal would mean for
stranded cost recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state is enduring under the cloud of an energy price
crisis,'' he said, ''I again call on the governor and my colleagues
in the Senate to come to the negotiating table and solve the energy
price crisis in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk is the third U.S. utility purchased by National
Grid, a London-based company created in 1990 following the breakup
of Britain's state-owned power system. National Grid builds, owns
and operates electric transmission and telecommunications networks
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, National Grid spent $3.2 billion to purchase
the New England Electric System, a utility with subsidiaries in
Massachusetts, Rhode Island and New Hampshire. New England
Electric, in turn, bought Eastern Utilities Associates, which
operates in Massachusetts and Rhode Island, for $642 million. The
merged companies became National Grid USA.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid USA expects that within four years it will save as
much as $90 million annually through consolidation and improved
efficiency across its New England and New York operations as a
result of the merger, said Richard Sergel, president and CEO of
National Grid USA.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately, all customers benefit if you can move the power
around and get the lowest-cost power being generated at any time,
Sergel said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed deal, which must receive approval from
shareholders of both companies as well as state and federal
regulators, Niagara Mohawk shareholders will receive about $19 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk stock opened the day trading on the New York
Stock Exchange at $17 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 billion represents a premium over the Niagara Mohawk's
market value of about $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction, which doubles the size of National Grid USA, is
expected to be completed by late 2001.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid USA will have a work force of approximately 10,000
once it absorbs about 6,200 Niagara Mohawk workers.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk will continue to search for a buyer for its two
Lake Ontario nuclear plants, which employ roughly 1,300 people.
Sergel said National Grid is not interested in the nuclear plants,
which are to be sold before completion of the acquisition. Over the
past two years, Niagara Mohawk has sold off all its fossil fuel and
hydro power plants as it transforms itself from an energy producer
into an energy supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Sergel said National Grid USA expected to reduce its overall
work force by between 500 and 750 workers over a four-year period
following completion of the purchase. He said the company expected
it could achieve those cuts through attrition and voluntary
programs and could avoid layoffs, although officials declined to
guarantee it.
</P>
<P>
   When it acquired New England Electric and EUA, National Grid USA
trimmed approximately 300 jobs without layoffs, Sergel said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is part of a trend as the country's energy industry
restructures itself.
</P>
<P>
   New York's largest power company, Con Edison, also is in the
process of being bought out by Connecticut-based Northeast
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio-based FirstEnergy Corp. recently announced the acquisition
of GPU Inc., which owns utilities in New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
And Entergy Corp. of Louisiana recently announced a merger with FPL
Group, the parent of Florida Power &AMP; Light, to create the nation's
largest electric company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1720 </TRAILER>
