<HEADLINE> Lost at sea: Five days later, still no sign of F-16 wreckage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIGANTINE, N.J. (AP) - Five days after it plunged into the
Atlantic Ocean, an F-16 fighter jet remained missing Tuesday,
eluding a salvage contractor scanning the ocean floor in search of
the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Tow, a marine salvage company based here, has been hired to
recover the jet, which is believed to be sunken in waters 1.5 miles
east of Brigantine.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of witnesses - including lifeguards, beachgoers and
others - watched Thursday as an Air National Guard pilot ditched
the plane in the water and ejected safely after developing engine
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the $18 million jet centered on a one-square mile
area of the ocean, according to Col. John Dwyer, spokesman for the
New Jersey Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ''They went to all those places where people said it crashed,
and we haven't located it. They're back out today,'' said Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   The jet, one of four planes from the 177th Fighter Wing on
training exercises over the ocean, was steered out to sea after the
pilot decided not to try a landing at Atlantic City International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, whose name hasn't been released, parachuted into the
ocean and was rescued unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the downed plane began Friday, with state police
divers setting out to map the debris field and determine the number
and size of the wreckage pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But it hadn't been found as of Tuesday afternoon, Dwyer said. He
compared the search to looking for a sunken pickup truck in a
square-mile area of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Tow officials did not return telephone calls seeking comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gusting northeasterly winds and choppy surf hampered the effort
Tuesday, according to an officer at the 177th Fighter Wing who
would not give his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
