<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nursing Homes Lobby for Funds  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government efforts to trim the growth of
Medicare payments are wreaking financial havoc on the nation's
nursing homes, industry leaders said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Already, five of the nation's 10 largest nursing home chains
have filed bankruptcy, nursing home advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bankruptcies among skilled nursing facilities have reached an
alarming figure,'' Dr. Charles Roadman II, president of the
American Health Care Association, told the Senate Special Committee
on Aging. ''This is just the tip of the iceberg. Our long term care
community is facing a squeeze with the real potential for absolute
collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders are lobbying the government to increase the
Medicare payments homes receive for patient care.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Charles Grassley, the Iowa Republican who heads the
committee, said he is unconvinced the nursing home industry needs
more money. President Clinton has proposed increasing Medicare
nursing home payments by about $1 billion over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said there is little evidence that patient care has
been jeopardized by Medicare reforms that took effect in 1998 and
established fixed payments for services.
</P>
<P>
   ''The nursing home industry blames the government for its
financial problems and wants more money,'' Grassley said. American
taxpayers contribute $39 billion annually in federal money to
nursing homes through Medicare and Medicaid, Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Some nursing home companies are suffering from bad business
decisions based on past practices where many Medicare
reimbursements from the government were essentially unlimited,
Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their investors and bankers gambled on a vision of
ever-growing government largesse,'' Grassley said. ''They got hurt
because this vision wasn't based on reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dummit, associate director of health financing and public
health issues for the General Accounting Office, said her agency's
study found that the new payment plan provides ''sufficient -- and
in some cases, even generous -- compensation for services furnished
to Medicare beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 17,000 nursing home in the United States. The five
companies that have gone bankrupt in the last two years -- Vencor,
Genesis Health Ventures, Sun Health Care, Integrated Health
Services and Mariner -- operate about 1,800 of those homes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, about 75 nursing home advocates rallied on the Capitol
steps to urge Congress to pass more funding. They complained of
staffing shortages and severely ill patients, who might require
expensive treatments, being turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm out on the front line,'' said Karen Shelangoski, a nurse
from Davenport, Iowa. ''They (lawmakers) don't know what it's all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1725 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico President Digs Up Past  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Soldiers open fire on thousands of peaceful
demonstrators. A presidential candidate is gunned down on a
campaign stop. The government spends $100 billion to buy overvalued
bad loans, some from its own supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has a lot of dirty laundry.
</P>
<P>
   During the 71 years that Mexico in effect had one-party rule,
the secrets lay buried. But now the Institutional Revolutionary
Party is out of office, and the new president, Vicente Fox, is
pledged to eradicate the corruption that pervades Mexican society.
</P>
<P>
   He says that one of the first things he will do after he is
sworn in Dec. 1 is have Mexico's Congress set up a ''Transparency
Commission'' to start digging into the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is essential for Mexico's new democracy,'' said Adolfo
Aguilar Zinser, a senator and key member of Fox's transition team.
''But this is a very difficult task.''
</P>
<P>
   It will also be the sternest test of Fox's credentials as a
reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the commission -- including how many cases it would
take on and what subpoena powers it might have -- have yet to be
worked out. But among the cases Congress could consider:
</P>
<P>
   --A banking scandal in which loans to ruling party supporters
were never repaid -- and then were absorbed by the government as
part of a $100 billion, taxpayer-funded bank bailout.
</P>
<P>
   --Lingering suspicions that shadowy, still-unidentified figures
might have played a part in several high-profile murders, including
that of ruling party presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio,
who was gunned down at a campaign stop in Tijuana in March 1994,
and that of Roman Catholic Cardinal Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo, who
died in a fusillade of bullets at Guadalajara's airport in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   --The stunning assault on a peaceful democracy protest Oct. 2,
1968, in Tlatelolco Plaza in Mexico City that killed hundreds. The
exact number of dead remains unknown, and it is unclear who ordered
a security battalion to open fire on the unarmed crowd of mostly
university students.
</P>
<P>
   Other unhealed wounds include the disappearance of hundreds of
leftists during an army crackdown on guerrilla bands in the 1970s,
the unsolved killings of hundreds of opposition party activists
over the past 12 years, and the work of domestic intelligence
agencies that opposition parties have long accused of political
spying.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that a war on big corruption will set an example
that will stamp out the petty corruption which people tend to take
as a harmless fact of everyday life. Motorists avoid a traffic
ticket by forking over a few dollars to the cop as casually as they
would tip a waiter. Bar owners slip an official a few hundred
dollars for a liquor license rather than take on the bureaucracy.
Some journalists support themselves with the money they receive for
writing favorable articles, and government purchasers pocket up to
10 percent of any contract.
</P>
<P>
   Delal Baer, a Mexico specialist at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington, sees a risky balancing act
ahead, lest the housecleaning become ''a witch hunt'' that could
bring the whole house down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mexico is in a bind,'' she said. ''You need to be careful not
to destroy your entire establishment because much of that
establishment is also good. But by the same token you need to meet
people's expectations that rule of law is not an empty promise.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk is that such a commission under the control of Congress
could get bogged down in politics and end in failure, dragging
Fox's administration down with it.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans aren't encouraged by the Italian example, in which a
sweeping corruption cleanup implicated so many politicians,
businessmen and bureaucrats that the courts were clogged and
accusations were made that the investigation had turned political.
</P>
<P>
   But Aguilar Zinser said Mexico's cleansing must involve all
political parties -- including Fox's National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the fear that given Mexico's record of political
violence, the deeper the investigators dig, the greater the
physical risk to them will be. ''Obviously this is going to be a
dangerous task,'' Aguilar Zinser said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jesus Zambrano, secretary-general of the leftist Democratic
Revolution Party, said an investigation is ''absolutely necessary
and indispensable in proving that the new government wants to
combat corruption and impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, everyone seems to welcome the idea, even the outgoing
government, which sees it as a means of regaining credibility. And
anyway, the plan is so popular that it would be political suicide
for anybody to oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he is sworn in, Fox's transitional team will hand
Congress a detailed proposal laying out the groundwork for the
investigation, including the constitutional reforms needed to give
lawmakers the legal muscle to carry it out.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will appoint the commission's members and choose the
cases to be investigated. An overhauled, more independent agency
modeled on the FBI will aid Congress and take on investigations of
private individuals who participated in government corruption,
Aguilar Zinser said.
</P>
<P>
   He said all cases with enough evidence will be handed over to
the courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1731 </TRAILER>
