<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study says workers' comp rates up for manufacturers  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Workers' compensation rates for
manufacturers were considerably higher in New York than the rest of
the nation during the last two years despite a state government
campaign to lower premiums, a business group said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that in the year ending Jan. 1, 2000, workers'
comp rates paid by manufacturers were just under 30 percent more
than the national average. New York's charge ranked 36 out of 45
states whose premium systems were comparable.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous year, which ended Jan. 1, 1999, New York
manufacturers paid workers' comp rates that were 20.9 percent
higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The national study is performed independently each year by
Actuarial &AMP; Technical Solutions of Ronkonkoma on Long Island and
its New York state numbers were analyzed by the Business Council
lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Business Council President Daniel Walsh said the statistics show
''we are moving in the wrong direction compared to competing
states'' on workers' comp rates. That is despite an effort begun in
1996 by Gov. George Pataki and the state Legislature to cut
workers' comp costs by improving workplace safety, limiting some
benefits, shifting premium costs onto higher-risk employers and
better fighting fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh called on government leaders in New York to take further
steps to cut workers' comp costs for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the report Tuesday, Pataki said he had not seen it
but will ''take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have to continue to look at ways to reform the
Workers' Compensation system,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has announced that as of Oct. 1, workers' comp
rates overall to be paid by all employers will fall by an average
of 2.5 percent, pushing the total reduction in New York rates to
almost 40 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Actuarial &AMP; Technical Solutions reported in 1996, before the
state's reform efforts, that workers' comp rate for manufacturers
were 57 percent above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Business Council spokesman Matthew Maguire said it is valid to
compare the workers' comp costs paid by manufacturers because they
have traditionally been such an important provider of jobs to New
Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently about 880,000 manufacturing jobs according
to the state Labor Department, or just over 10 percent of the
state's private and public job force.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggests that other states are doing better than New
York at lowering workers' comp costs for manufacturers, Maguire
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether we're not doing enough here and other states are doing
more, the fact is we are losing ground to the national average,''
Maguire said. ''If New York state's workers' comp costs improved,
but other states' costs improved more, then our relative position
suffers. That's important.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that New York benefits were 38th best out
of 50 states, almost 27 percent higher than the national average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1731 </TRAILER>
