<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 22; Nasdaq Falls 91  </HEADLINE>
By LISA SINGHANIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A poor outlook for technology and pharmaceutical
stocks prompted heavy selling in those sectors Tuesday, the only
notable activity in an otherwise lackluster session.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which is heavily concentrated in
technology issues, fell 91.15 to 4,143.18, giving back nearly half
its 191-point gain of last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 21.83 at 11,260.61,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index slipped 13.69 to 1,507.08.
</P>
<P>
   With no big news to provide a clear direction for trading, the
market meandered. Indexes alternated between positive and negative
territory throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''September has typically been a very unclear month for the
market and after the very nice run we had in August, we've got some
profit-taking and maybe some developing concerns about reports for
third-quarter earnings,'' said Bill Barker, an investment strategy
consultant with Dain Rauscher Inc. in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions were the pharmaceutical and tech sectors, which
declined overall.
</P>
<P>
   Intel fell $4.69 to $69.25 after a U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray
analyst downgraded the computer chip maker's stock to ''buy'' from
''strong buy. Ashok Kumar said he was concerned that continued weak
demand could result in lower-than-expected sales growth. He was
also concerned about the potential for oversupply.
</P>
<P>
   Computer maker stocks also fell on the news, with Gateway
dropping $4.71 to $63.97 and Dell off $2.06 at $41.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can see the Nasdaq is down hard,'' said Peter Anderson,
chief investment officer at American Express Financial Advisors in
Minneapolis. ''The tech stocks have been the favorite. They've had
big runs. What you're witnessing is some type of a correction.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical stocks fell slightly after Banc of America
Securities downgraded Merck to ''market perform'' from ''strong
buy'' and, at the same time, reduced estimates for the overall drug
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Merck fell $1.13 to $68.06. Pfizer, one of the most actively
traded stocks on the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday, was down
$2.16 at $41.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of these stocks have been pretty strong performers and I
think there is some concerns about the political rhetoric,''
Anderson said. The cost of prescription drugs and Medicare coverage
for them have become issues in this fall's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Other active stocks Tuesday included Intermedia Communications.
Its shares rose $8.61, or 37.6 percent, to $31.48 after WorldCom
said it was acquiring Intermedia for $3 billion in stock and cash.
The deal also includes Intermedia's controlling stake in Digex, a
leading operator of computer centers that run Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher Scientific International's shares jumped $9.63, about
43.9 percent, to $31.56. The company announced late Friday its $800
million plan to buy PSS World Medical, another medical products
distributor, had fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Niagara Mohawk Holdings rose $1.88 to $15.75 after
British-based National Grid Group announced it was buying the
utility for $3 billion in cash and stock. Niagara Mohawk is the
second-largest electric and gas provider in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a small margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 836.26 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 2.89 to 539.02.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.41 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 0.67 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
down 0.67 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
