<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cops on duty at West Indian parade suspended for drinking  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Two police officers were suspended for allegedly
drinking beer while on-duty at this year's West Indian American Day
Parade, the first year alcohol was banned from the event, police
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officers Anthony Zayas, 36, and Kevin Kryzak, 39, both assigned
to the 44th Precinct in the Morris Heights section of the Bronx,
were suspended without pay for a maximum of 30 days for consuming
alcohol while in uniform. Zayas has been on the force for 14 years,
Kryzak for 15.
</P>
<P>
   The officers had been assigned to work the parade detail Sunday
from 6:40 a.m. to 3:15 p.m., but were held over on overtime. Around
9:30 p.m., the sergeant in charge of the officers' sector smelled
alcohol on their breath, and watched as they walked into the
Rodriguez Grocery Store on Bedford Avenue, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant went into the store and saw the officers in a
backroom allegedly holding half-full bottles of Corona beer, police
said. Three empty bottles were strewn near them, but it was
uncertain if the officers had consumed them.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parade had officially ended at 6 p.m., there were
still many people milling about the area, attending various
festivities at 9:30 p.m. Nearly 2 million revelers attended the
annual parade, a New York City tradition since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   There was little trouble - police issued 95 summonses, most for
alcohol-related infractions. They made 10 arrests - two men were
arrested for groping women at the parade and two other men were
arrested for fighting along the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration ordered a series of safety measures
at this year's parade after two children and an adult were struck
and killed last year by floats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
