<HEADLINE> Corzine begins air war as Franks ducks questions about campaign finances </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Democratic U.S. Senate candidate Jon
Corzine has launched his TV advertising, a blitz that will probably
cost as much in its first week as his Republican opponent has
raised so far for his whole campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine campaign spokesman Tom Shea refused to provide any
details on how much was being spent on the TV spots, although he
did confirm they started running Monday on both New York and
Philadelphia network-affiliated TV stations.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine typically spent $1 million to $1.5 million a week on TV
spots during the Democratic primary campaign on the road to
defeating former Gov. Jim Florio. The $36.7 million he spent to
beat Florio set a national record for spending in any race for
Congress in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Inquirer last week reported the spending on TV
ads would be about $1 million this week. Rider University political
analyst David Rebovich said it was logical Corzine would spend at
least that much since some recent polls have shown Franks gaining
ground on him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why would he scale it down now'' compared with the primary,
Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Franks refused Tuesday to comment on published reports that his
fund-raising had been less than expected, but campaign manager
Charlie Smith said it had surpassed $1 million. Franks would not
say when he would or could begin buying time on TV, and Smith said
such fund-raising and spending details would be withheld until the
campaign is required to make them public Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's TV spot is warm and biographical, showing Corzine
meeting and laughing with a variety of voter groups while
campaigning. The ad summarizes the candidate's promises on an array
of issues in 60-second and 30-second versions. It does not mention
Franks nor contain any harsh language about disputes in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Franks' staff fired back anyway Tuesday, charging the Corzine
ads say he is the only candidate in the race promising to protect
Social Security, help seniors afford drugs or help pay for college.
Franks' staff noted the congressman's voting record in support of
measures for all of those steps.
</P>
<P>
   While Corzine took to the air Tuesday, Franks was on the
Statehouse steps with officials of the Fraternal Order of Police,
the state's second-largest police union, who endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is scheduled to appear at the Statehouse Wednesday to
accept the endorsement of the Sierra Club, which had backed Florio
in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the FOP endorsement, president Richard Whelan
praised Franks for his accessibility to them during eight years in
Congress. Whelan complained Corzine had been unwilling to meet
personally with union officers who wanted to interview him.
</P>
<P>
   Whelan could not say if members of the police union find any of
Corzine's proposals objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, however, energetically denounced Corzine for his
opposition to the death penalty. ''There is nothing soft or
ambiguous about my position on crime,'' Franks said, adding he
believes New Jersey voters want murderers who prey on the young,
for instance, to face execution.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said, ''Jon has a strong philosophical opposition to it,
and he thinks enough of the voters of New Jersey that even if they
don't agree with him on the issue, they will respect the fact that
he is willing to take a principled stand on something he believes
in strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks boasted of his votes on the 1994 Crime Bill to toughen
criminal laws and fund the hiring of new police officers. Shea said
Franks in 1995 voted on a Republican bill to repeal that same
funding for police officers.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
