<HEADLINE> Corzine's friendly ad reintroduces him, his issues to voters  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   EDITOR'S NOTE: One of a series looking at commercials
run in the
campaign for U.S. Senate in New Jersey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE: Democrat Jon Corzine
</P>
<P>
   AD FIRM: Shrum, Devine &AMP; Donilon, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: 60-second television ad.
</P>
<P>
   TEXT:
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ''From diners to the Shore to senior centers to our
schools, he's sat with us, listened to us, talked with us, and told
us what he'd do. Jon Corzine. He's the candidate who says we have
to put Social Security in a lock box where the politicians can't
touch it. He's the one who supports a guaranteed prescription drug
benefit under Medicare, and a real patients' bill of rights for all
our citizens. He's the one who favors universal preschool and
setting higher standards in our schools. He's had the courage to
call for licensing and registering all guns, and to stand up to
protect the rights of us all. He has the fiscal discipline of a
successful businessman, and the faith in the American Dream of
someone who had to work for everything he's gotten in life.
Standing with us. Fighting for us. Jon Corzine in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO:
</P>
<P>
   Corzine moves around rooms, sits with voters and pumps a fist,
usually in casual dress, as issue points are printed on a bar
designed to not interfere with the picture. In two scenes children
and police are seen as the text addresses preschools and gun
licensing.
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGY:
</P>
<P>
   Seeks to reintroduce voters to Corzine and to show he has been
actively campaigning. Implies Corzine is the only one seeking to
protect Social Security and to win drug benefits for seniors, not
GOP opponent Bob Franks. Ad does this without mentioning Franks,
which would give the opponent free name recognition. Deletes ''bold
ideas'' slogan of the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   FACT-CHECK:
</P>
<P>
   Since the June 6 primary Corzine has remained largely outside
the public eye except at the Democratic National Convention, where
he was prominent. For that matter, so has Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Franks in his campaign also has been promising to protect Social
Security and provide drug benefits to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine did not inherit family money, but at Goldman Sachs he
was fortunate enough to be awarded posts that earned him fabulous
wealth as the firm expanded. He spent $6 million more to win the
June primary than any congressional candidate in American history
had ever spent in a whole year, which could make it difficult for
some to link him with the phrase ''fiscal discipline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
