<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental group endorses Clinton over Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) - In a major disappointment for the
Lazio campaign, the Sierra Club, an important environmental group,
endorsed Hillary Rodham Clinton for Senate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio has been viewed as an ally in the past by other
groups like the League of Conservation Voters for his work on
cleaning up Long Island Sound and fighting strip-mining. But Sierra
Club official Rhea Jezer said he ''has dropped the ball on many key
environmental issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Jezer, conservation chair of the Sierra Club's Atlantic Chapter,
which includes New York, added: ''Although he has a few
environmental achievements, Rep. Lazio's overall batting average
puts him in the bottom third of our state's delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Lazio, at a Manhattan press conference, said: ''I'm
very proud of my environmental record as an author of major
environmental legislation, as somebody who has voted against both
Republican and Democratic anti-environmental riders.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Tuesday, while campaigning in Rochester, Lazio said he
''can't think of a single time when Mrs. Clinton has ever
forcefully spoke out on any environmental issue.''
</P>
<P>
   His campaign manager Bill Dal Col pointed out his fights to
enforce the Clean Water Act and the Clean Air Act, and questioned
Clinton's commitment to environmental issues. The first lady has
made education, health care and abortion rights among the major
themes of her campaign but has focused less on environmental
issues. Dal Col also noted that Lazio was named one of the League
of Conservation Voters' 10 ''Environmental Heroes'' in 1998, and
that the Sierra Club endorsed him in 1996. ''The fact is that Mrs.
Clinton has no identifiable environmental record,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmentalists cited a series of votes by Lazio that
they disagreed with, including votes against amendments to
strengthen cleanup standards at toxic waste sites covered by the
Superfund program; against a bill that would allow local officials
to request cleanup of a site without their governors approval; and
against an amendment to curb suburban sprawl by protecting open
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Senate, New Yorkers will be able to count on Hillary
Clinton to do what's right to protect our families from toxic
pollution. With Rep. Rick Lazio, we don't have that confidence,''
said Robert Cox, national president of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club's New York leaders conducted lengthy separate
interviews with each candidate before making their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''This endorsement is extremely important. I know I was not
alone in seeking it,'' said Clinton, appearing with Sierra Club
officials at Five Islands Park, an inlet off Long Island Sound in
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Clinton over Lazio, the group's officials cited her
commitment to cleaning up Long Island Sound, the Hudson River,
reducing pollution from power plant smokestacks, and conserving New
York's watershed lands to avoid filtration plants.
</P>
<P>
   Jezer also complained that Lazio ''just doesn't seem to be aware
of many of the local issues,'' and cited the controversy over
whether a filtration plant is needed as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan pointed out that the organization
has not endorsed a Republican in a statewide election in at least a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dal Col went to Albany to unveil a new television
spot attacking an earlier Clinton ad that featured comments from
people who had been described as randomly chosen New Yorkers. It
turned out a woman featured in the ad is a former employee of a
Democratic state Assembly member. The Lazio ad, titled ''Ringer,''
ends with the line, ''Another phony ad from Hillary Clinton. You
just can't trust her.''
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col also was in Albany to speak to the Republican State
Committee, an attempt to calm fears among GOP leaders that the
congressman hasn't been campaigning enough. Lazio took a four-day
vacation with his family in the posh Hamptons on the east end of
Long Island just before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best way to answer the criticism up front is Rick's done
enough that we raised $10.7 million in the last 58 days ... If you
don't have the resources to take on the onslaught that she's put
together, we'd get buried,'' Dal Col told Albany's WROW-AM radio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio raised more than three times what Clinton pulled in during
July and August.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio aide also promised that over the next several weeks,
''You'll see him come forward with some bold proposals on
education, health care (and) Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Lazio appeared in Manhattan with Gov. George Pataki and
U.S. Reps. Jerrold Nadler, Nita Lowey and Carolyn Maloney to call
for the release of 10 Jews who were convicted in Iran of spying for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Lazio visited the home of a Republican couple
with two young children in Greece, a Rochester suburb, to talk
about his tax plan, which he estimates will save an average family
$1,200 a year in payroll taxes alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't ever save money ... we get so little back,'' Rebecca
Caracci, a 27-year-old elementary school teacher, told the
congressman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
