<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firm Buys Ads for Labor, Candidates  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government has cleared the Democratic
Party and labor unions of illegally coordinating their 1996
campaign activities, and the firm that played a key role in that
investigation is back to buying TV ads for both unions and
candidates, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Denver-based Media Strategies and Research bought almost $16,000
worth of advertising time on a Charlotte, N.C., television station
in July for the AFL-CIO. The union ran ads urging Republican Rep.
Robin Hayes to support legislation imposing new regulations on
managed-care health organizations, according to copies of checks
provided by the National Republican Congressional Committee. A
month later, the company spent almost $8,000 buying ads for Hayes'
Democratic challenger, Mike Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes defeated Taylor by just 3,000 votes in 1998, and the
rematch is one of the fall's most competitive contests.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's media producer, Jim Duffy, said the firm was no longer
placing labor ads in the congressional district now that it is
working for the Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC singled out Media Strategies as part of its
investigation because the firm placed ads for the AFL-CIO in the
districts of three candidates the company worked for in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission said there was no evidence of illegal
coordination because AFL-CIO officials made their own decisions as
to where and when to run the ads and didn't know that the media
firm also was working for the congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ran counter to an FEC ruling in 1980 which said
that an outside group's ability to make independent expenditures
was compromised if it shared a media buying firm with a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission said it was being guided by a 1999 U.S.
District Court decision that threw out most of its case against the
Christian Coalition. Judge Joyce Green rejected arguments that the
group improperly coordinated its activities with candidates by
alerting them in advance to the voter guides its distributed and
telephone get-out-the-vote drives.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the FEC noted that the AFL-CIO regularly met with
Democratic Party officials and reviewed plans for the fall
campaign. But the commission said the practice violated no laws
because neither the Democrats nor their candidates asked the
AFL-CIO for any specific activities on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ''The news here is that the FEC dismissed all of the charges,''
AFL-CIO Political Director Steve Rosenthal said. ''As long as there
have been coordinated campaigns, there has been a review process
here at the AFL-CIO. As major contributors to these campaign plans,
we decided years ago that it made sense to review them and make
suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   NRCC spokesman Jim Wilkinson criticized the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''All along, we thought the Democrats worked with the unions,''
Wilkinson said. ''We had no idea that the Democrats worked for the
unions. Democrats clearly think they're above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is important because outside organizations can make
unlimited independent expenditures, but are severely limited as to
how much they can spend if they coordinate their actions with a
candidate or political party.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said there was nothing wrong with sharing media
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a limited number of firms that do this work and do
it right,'' Rosenthal said. ''How about firms that do work for the
NRCC and Republican candidates and the NFIB (National Federation of
Small Business) and the Chamber of Commerce and the various
citizens' groups that pop up all the time on their side of the
aisle?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1904 </TRAILER>
