<HEADLINE> New Jersey accountant admits he stalked ''Suddenly Susan'' actress  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA DEUTSCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - A New Jersey accountant admitted in court
Tuesday that he stalked actress Brooke Shields and made terrorist
threats against her, then entered a plea of no contest.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bailey was ordered to leave California and return to his
home state, where he will remain on probation for five years. He
had already served nearly a year in jail. With credit for good
behavior, he is eligible for immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   He was also ordered to undergo psychiatric counseling twice a
week, to take medication as prescribed by his doctor and to report
to a probation officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''You must not harass or molest the victim or threaten use of
force or violence against anyone,'' Superior Court Judge Maureen
Duffy-Lewis told him.
</P>
<P>
   She told Bailey he may not have contact with Shields, her
agents, family or representatives for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Shields has said Bailey harassed her for 15 years - sending her
nude photos of himself and letters threatening her with harm.
</P>
<P>
   Shields, who did not attend Tuesday's court hearing, submitted a
statement which was read in court expressing her gratitude to the
district attorney's office and saying, ''I believe that no one in
our society should have to live in constant terror and fear. ... I
simply seek only peace of mind and personal safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Scott Gordon said the prosecution
agreed to a plea bargain only after adding a charge of making
terrorist threats. That qualified Bailey's plea as a first strike
under California's three-strikes law and would subject him to
stronger penalties if he is convicted again.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, 41, has two prior convictions involving Shields, one for
trespassing at her New Jersey home in 1985 and another for making a
terrorist threat against her in 1993. But the three-strikes law was
not in effect at the time of either crime.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested Jan. 10 after detectives said they saw him pull
a handgun out of his pocket while looking at his reflection outside
a building in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that when Bailey was taken into custody he had
two letters he was about to mail to Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's lawyer, Deputy Public Defender Lisa Polansky said
outside court that Bailey understands he must submit to psychiatric
and medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to address the problem which seems to be
treatable through medication,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shields, 35, recently became engaged to producer Chris Henchy.
She was previously married to tennis ace Andre Agassi. NBC canceled
Shields' show, ''Suddenly Susan,'' earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
