<HEADLINE> Sabres' Peca May Look Elsewhere  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Captain Michael Peca and the Buffalo Sabres
are far apart in contract talks three days before the team opens
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a difference of opinion. The distinction is
substantial,'' Peca's agent, Don Meehan, said Tuesday. Meehan said
he might explore ''other options'' depending on how negotiations
go.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's considering demanding a trade, the agent said,
''We're not there yet. I won't speculate until we get to that point
in the future. It's better to comment on those options once we've
exhausted our discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca, a restricted free agent, is seeking a two- to four-year
deal worth about $4 million annually, more than double the $1.65
million he made last season.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres general manager Darcy Regier hoped a deal can be reached
within days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's a great surprise to anybody, but the
biggest difference is money,'' Regier said. ''We've got a lot of
things on the table, and we've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca is coming off a subpar season, with 20 goals and 41 points
in 73 games. In 1997, he was named the NHL's best defensive
forward, and in 1998-99 he was credited for helping lead the
Sabres' drive to the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres have four other unsigned restricted free agents:
backup goalie Martin Biron, forward Erik Rasmussen, forward Denis
Hamel and defenseman Jason Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Regier said he's also had numerous talks this week in trying to
re-sign unrestricted free agent Vladimir Tsyplakov, who was
productive for Buffalo -- six goals and 19 points in 34 games --
after being acquired in midseason from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sabres have settled on a one-year deal to renew
their affiliation agreement with the American Hockey League's
Rochester Americans. Regier said the club is looking for a
longer-term deal with the Americans, who have been the Sabres'
minor league farm team for 21 seasons -- pro hockey's longest
affiliation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
