<DOCNO> APW20000905.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rams' Defense Falters in Opener  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Just like last season, the St. Louis Rams have
no problem scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Playing against this offense instead of watching it is very
hard,'' said Denver Broncos strong safety Billy Jenkins, who played
for the Rams last year. ''Those guys are some of the most elusive
guys in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   But in their season-opening 41-36 victory over the Broncos on
Monday night, the Rams had to make plays to compensate for a
defense that sprung several leaks. The Rams rolled up 513 yards,
had scoring plays of 86, 72 and 80 yards and had three 100-yard
receivers in the same game for the first time since 1951.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have high standards on offense,'' first-year coach Mike
Martz said. ''I think we approached those standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet they beat the Broncos by only five points. Blame it on a
defense that ranked fourth in the NFL in points allowed last year,
giving up 15 points a game, and lost one player from that unit.
</P>
<P>
   Martz wasn't concerned the day after the Rams allowed 424 yards,
partly because it was the opener and partly because the Broncos
have a high-powered attack. He said he had no trouble getting
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me tell you this, that's a good offense, that's a real
good offense, and they'll score a lot of points,'' Martz said of
Denver. ''That's not to say we're not a good defense. We're going
to be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   They will be without tackle D'Marco Farr for about a month after
he tore knee cartilage against the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Farr, who has started every game since the Rams moved to St.
Louis in 1995, was injured in the fourth quarter. He will have
surgery Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some Rams players felt Jenkins was a big part of their problem
because he knows the defense so well. The Broncos didn't do much
exotic on offense, but were able to find the holes in the St. Louis
zone all night.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos quarterback Brian Griese was 19-of-29 for 307 yards and
two touchdowns. He hit Ed McCaffrey seven times for 115 yards and
Rod Smith three times for 88.
</P>
<P>
   ''Denver got us in a couple situations where they knew exactly
what we were doing and just attacked the weakness,'' cornerback
Todd Lyght said. ''Obviously, we have a lot of things we have to
work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Martz said the linebackers and secondary share the blame. Middle
linebacker London Fletcher, who had two sacks and nine solo
tackles, said he was out of position when the Broncos got a 38-yard
pass play to tight end Byron Chamberlain on third-and-16 from the
Denver 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was my bust,'' Fletcher said. ''I was trying to do too
much. That's something I've got to continue to work on, staying
disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos also muted the Rams' pass rush, which tied for the
league lead in sacks last year, until late in the game when they
sacked Griese twice and Grant Wistrom hit him as he delivered his
final pass on fourth-and-33 from the Denver 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams weren't able to blitz as often as Martz would have
liked because they respected the Broncos' running game. Denver
stayed with two wideouts and two tight ends most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's always that threat that ball is going to be handed
off,'' Martz said. ''If there's a crease, there's nobody back
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was the third straight nail-biting finish for the
Rams, who edged Tampa Bay 11-6 in the NFC championship game and got
a overtime-saving tackle a yard-and-a-half away from the end zone
by Mike Jones in their 23-16 Super Bowl victory over the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Those three games were nothing like most of last season for the
Rams, who won by an average of 33-15 while scoring the
third-highest point total in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm ready for some more blowouts,'' Wistrom said. ''I'm tired
of these tight games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1915 </TRAILER>
