<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug maker accuses competitor of antitrust violations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CINCINNATI (AP) - Duramed Pharmaceuticals Inc. alleged in a
lawsuit Tuesday that rival Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories violated
antitrust laws and furthered a monopoly of its drug Premarin by
undercutting sales of Duramed's competing Cenestin.
</P>
<P>
   Both prescription drugs are designed to relieve symptoms of
menopause, including hot flashes and night sweats.
</P>
<P>
   Duramed accused Wyeth-Ayerst of making contracts for sales of
Premarin and setting prices and discounts on the condition that
health plans not buy Cenestin.
</P>
<P>
   That conduct has substantially reduced competition, helping
Wyeth-Ayerst maintain a monopoly and more than $800 million in
annual U.S. sales of Premarin, Duramed said in the lawsuit filed
Tuesday in Cincinnati federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst also cost Duramed millions of dollars with a
misleading political and public relations campaign to stall federal
approval of Cenestin for five years, Duramed's lawsuit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Duramed, based in Cincinnati, asked the U.S. District Court for
an order to stop Wyeth-Ayerst's alleged wrongdoing. The company
also asked for unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst spokeswoman Audrey Ashby, at the company's suburban
Philadelphia headquarters, declined to discuss the lawsuit.
Wyeth-Ayerst is a division of American Home Products Corp., which
is based in Madison, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Premarin is derived from the urine of pregnant mares. Duramed
contends that its plant-derived Cenestin would have created market
competition as a less expensive alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst has made Premarin since 1942. Duramed said
Wyeth-Ayerst increased the price of Premarin 12 percent - 5&AMP;frac12; times
the rate of inflation - between January 1999 and January 2000 and
raised it again by 6 percent on March 29 of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 1919 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skelton Calls for Navy Overhaul  </HEADLINE>
By LIB QUAID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Smaller, lighter, faster ships are the future
of the U.S. Navy, a senior House Armed Services Committee member
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know that some find it hard or even distasteful to imagine a
Navy with smaller ships,'' Missouri Rep. Ike Skelton, the panel's
senior Democrat, said Tuesday in prepared remarks. ''But it is
harder and more repugnant to imagine a Navy rendered irrelevant by
a focus on yesterday's missions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army is under fire on Capitol Hill for proposing a similar
initiative to retain heavy forces while giving light forces more
punch. Both service branches are facing the same challenge, Skelton
said: ''The force we have today and the missions we are actually
taking on do not match.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks were a major policy statement from Skelton, one of
the Navy's most influential supporters in Congress. The 12-term
lawmaker spoke during a dinner hosted by Business Executives for
National Security and attended by senior Navy officials.
</P>
<P>
   '''In close' is where the threat lives today -- the missiles that
threaten our battle groups, the speedboats and small lighters used
for hit and run raids, the many light craft now used to place
mines,'' Skelton said.
</P>
<P>
   In shaping its future, the Navy is spending a lot of money
studying the wisdom of such an approach, said Cmdr. Brian Cullin,
spokesman for Navy Secretary Richard Danzig.
</P>
<P>
   While many argue that defense spending is more than adequate,
the same critics are the first to call for intervention in crises
around the globe, Skelton said. Yet the overall fleet will sink
below 300 before the decade is out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Demand for naval forces hasn't gone away with the Cold War; it
has increased,'' Skelton said. ''If we're missing missions today,
how dire will the situation will be with a 200-ship fleet?''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy forces should be maintained to safeguard the ''blue
water'' deep at sea, but smaller, lighter, faster platforms are
needed to take the fight to shore, Skelton said. The military has
building plans for medium and large ships, he said, but the most
efficient way to build numbers in the fleet and meet the presence
requirement is to start a class of smaller hulls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
