<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Arafat Should Show Gains  </HEADLINE>
By IBRAHIM BARZAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Yasser Arafat must bring back real
gains from meetings with President Clinton in New York if he wants
to delay a Sept. 13 deadline for statehood, a senior Palestinian
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Central Council chairman Selim Zanoun said the body
would need at least two promises before it would put off
declaration of a state.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, Israel would have to promise to hand over West
Bank territory, as it pledged in an earlier agreement. Also, he
said, the United States and Israel would have to agree to allow the
Palestinians to set up their state by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Central Council is to meet this weekend to
decide about declaring a state. Palestinian officials have strongly
hinted that the council will approve the delay, but Zanoun said it
was not a given.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PCC will not agree to a delay without serious
obligations,'' he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has threatened to unilaterally
annex West Bank land if the Palestinians declare statehood on Sept.
13. That would likely lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
   The jockeying came ahead of Clinton's efforts this week to
reconvene a Mideast summit. Clinton is meeting separately with
Palestinian leader Arafat and Barak on Wednesday during the U.N.
Millennium summit in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Communications Minister Binyamin Ben Eliezer, a Barak confidant,
said the prime minister had conceded enough at the Camp David
summit in July.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality right now is that we are just waiting for answers
from the other side,'' Ben Eliezer told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he would propose bringing the hard-line
opposition Likud party into his government if there is no agreement
by the end of October, when parliament reconvenes.
</P>
<P>
   Barak leads a minority government, and bringing the Likud in
would be one way to survive efforts to topple him -- but it would
chill the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Barak lost the support of hawkish parties because of the
far-reaching proposals at Camp David -- he broke long-standing
taboos by even discussing Jerusalem and the return of Palestinian
refugees. Arafat also breached a taboo by tentatively agreeing to
Israel keeping some West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem issue collapsed the talks. Palestinians and
Israelis could not agree how to divide the walled Old City in the
city's traditionally Arab eastern sector. The Old City houses some
of the holiest sites in Judaism, Christianity and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been pressing for a solution that would defer a
decision for several years. That has been welcomed by the Israelis,
but the Palestinians have insisted that Jerusalem -- where they want
to set up a capital -- should be part of a final package.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a top Palestinian negotiator, Ahmed Qureia, proposed
internationalizing all Jerusalem pending agreement on how to share
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless we can reach an agreement on Jerusalem, I have to
declare that both parts of Jerusalem east and west should be a
unified international Jerusalem ... not just the capital of Israel
or Palestine, but a capital of the world,'' Qureia told the
626-member European Parliament in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Palestinians proposed anything close
to the U.S. proposal to delay discussing the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami rejected the idea.
''There is no such thing'' as an international city, he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami said both sides must have symbolic sovereignty on the
hill where holy sites are located. He told Israel television that
Israel wants an arrangement that ''preserves the actual situation
on the ground but gives symbolic satisfaction to both sides, and
this can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel claims sovereignty there, but the Islamic religious
council, or Wakf, administers the Muslim sites.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's deputy foreign minister, Nawaf Massalha, said ''the
problem is between the Israelis and the Palestinians or the Jews
and the Arabs, and they have to solve it,'' he said. ''It's not the
international community's problem ... It is our problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, King Abdullah II of Jordan encouraged Palestinians
and Israelis to work toward a peace settlement, saying a window of
opportunity to end decades of conflict in the Middle East should
not be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah's comments, made through a spokesman, came after a
brief meeting with Barak in tight security at a midtown Manhattan
hotel. The two are in New York to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The king and the prime minister agreed that Arafat would have to
make ''final decisions regarding outstanding issues in the peace
process,'' Barak's office said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 1945 </TRAILER>
