<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Defends Charitable Donations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Dick Cheney defended his direct
contributions to charities, which accounted for less than 1 percent
of the $4 million he earned last year, saying donations are a
matter of private choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a choice that individuals have to make in terms of what
they want to do with their resources,'' the GOP vice presidential
candidate said Tuesday. ''I thought it was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the donations arose after Cheney, running mate
for George W. Bush, released personal tax records for himself and
his wife Lynne last week showing that $442,152 went to charities
from 1989 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half of the amount, $209,832, were direct,
out-of-pocket contributions to charities. Cheney said the donations
went to United Way, a scholarship fund for inner city kids, and
other charities.
</P>
<P>
   Another $89,500 were honorariums for speeches that were declined
and requested to be donated to charities. In addition, $142,820 was
requested as matches for charitable contributions from corporations
on whose boards the Cheneys sit.
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years in government jobs, Cheney, a former defense
secretary and congressman, joined Halliburton Co. in 1995 as chief
executive officer. Last year he and his wife, a writer and research
fellow, reported gross income of $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney have urged support of faith-based organizations
and charities that provide services to cure social problems and
help poor people.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said the appropriate level of giving is up to the
individual.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a private matter ... a matter of private choice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife Laura gave $334,000 in donations in 1998, the
last year figures were available, representing just under 2 percent
of their taxable income of $18.4 million that year.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore and his wife Tipper
gave $15,000 to charity in 1998, representing nearly 7 percent of
their taxable income of $224,000.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and his wife criticized in 1997 for
contributing only $353 to charity, after giving away more than
$35,000 the year before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
