<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tests show horse died from West Nile Virus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A horse on a Cape May county farm is New
Jersey's first confirmed death from the West Nile Virus, state
agriculture officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tests show the 6-year-old thoroughbred gelding died from the
virus and complications from other illnesses, Agriculture Secretary
Art Brown said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The horse became ill Wednesday and was euthanized Saturday.
Symptoms like high fever and unusually aggressive behavior prompted
the test, according to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Owners reported that the horse did not leave their Tuckahoe farm
for the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brown, horses only become infected with the virus
when bitten by a mosquito and not all horses become ill. The
sometimes fatal disease can't be spread to humans from infected
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the state Health Department said a Jersey City man was
the first in the state to be infected. Seven people in New York
have died from the disease this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
