<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge declines to toss out lawsuit seeking to permit wholesale wine sales </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An effort by out-of-state wineries to strike
down a New York State law preventing them from selling directly to
New York consumers cleared its first hurdle when a judge refused
Tuesday to toss it out.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard M. Berman declined to rule on the
merits of the issue but he did cite successful challenges of
similar laws in other states, including Indiana, Illinois and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said even though there had been an evolution in the
way the courts have treated liquor sale cases, including a 1984
Supreme Court case in which the justices rejected state statutes
that discriminated against interstate commerce, he said it was
''too early to assess definitively the wisdom and correctness of
these other rulings.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not too early for the plaintiffs to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's David 1, Goliath nothing,'' said Clint Bolick, litigation
director for the Institute for Justice, a nonprofit law firm which
brought the case on behalf of wineries in Virginia and California
and three New York State consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Bolick said he expected the New York case would be a significant
battle ground for the law, which is similar to statutes in 29 other
states.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York is the largest of those states and the wholesaler
industry seems to be circling the wagons in New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the firms sued the New York State Liquor Authority,
seeking to overturn the Direct Shipment and Advertising Ban, a law
which its says prevents out-of-state wineries from obtaining a
license to distribute alcoholic beverages directly to consumers in
New York State and from advertising their wines directly to New
York consumers, even on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left with a spokesman for New York State
Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   After the lawsuit was filed, others joined it to defend the law,
including four large wholesalers, a union, a package store
association and an activist who has fought in the past to keep
liquor and cigarettes out of Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   They had argued that the law was Constitutional and necessary to
regulate liquor sales in New York State, including keeping liquor
away from those under the age of 21.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like most states, New York has long required that imported
liquors be distributed here only through licensed wholesalers and
retailers for good reasons,'' said lawyer Randy Mastro, reading a
statement he issued jointly with a second attorney.
</P>
<P>
   He said the law was necessary to ensure accountability and
responsibility, to make sure the liquor market was orderly and to
collect taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are legitimate state interests that we are confident the
court will ultimately find our Constitution protects,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-05-00 2034 </TRAILER>
