<HEADLINE> Chargers Sign Smith To Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The San Diego Chargers signed former Kansas
City and Denver defensive end Neil Smith to a two-year contract
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the agreement were not released.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will begin his 13th season in the AFC West. He spent the
last three years with the Broncos, making 34 tackles and 6&AMP;frac12; sacks
in eight games last season. He played with Denver's Super Bowl
champion teams in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining the Broncos, Smith spent nine years with the
Chiefs and was part of their playoff run from 1990 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It took almost two weeks to reach the contract agreement with
Smith, who first visited the Chargers camp on Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's visit may have seemed well-timed, as the Chargers had
just lost their leading pass rusher, Raylee Johnson, to a
season-ending knee injury. Johnson had a career-high 10&AMP;frac12; sacks last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The signing became even more urgent after defensive end Al
Fontenot injured a calf in the Chargers' 9-6 season-opening loss to
Oakland on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not expected to practice with the Chargers until
Thursday, as his wife gave birth to a girl Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has started 162 NFL games and played in 181 since being
the No. 2 overall draft pick in 1988. He has 664 tackles, 104&AMP;frac12;
sacks and four interceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
