<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Sox Likely Without Eldred  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Cal Eldred's comeback from a nerve problem in his
troublesome right elbow apparently is over for this year.
</P>
<P>
   While the Chicago White Sox awaited results of a bone scan on
Eldred's elbow Tuesday, manager Jerry Manuel said he's not counting
on having the veteran right-hander for the final 3&AMP;frac12; weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Eldred, who had ligament replacement surgery while with Brewers
in 1995, has been on the disabled list since July 17. It's his
sixth trip to the DL in five years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the primary reasons for the White Sox's fast start,
Eldred was 10-2 with two complete games and a shutout this season.
He came to Chicago in a trade along with shortstop Jose Valentin
for Jaime Navarro and John Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Eldred was throwing like his pre-surgery days when he
won 11, 16 and 11 games for the Brewers from 1992-94.
</P>
<P>
   But on July 14 while pitcing against the Cardinals, he felt pain
in his elbow in the fifth inning and had to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   That sent Eldred on another comeback and he had made progress,
so much in fact he hoped to pitch this Friday against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But during his second rehab start Sunday at Triple-A Charlotte,
the pain returned and Eldred pulled himself out after two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ''He felt something. He did the right thing and took himself
out,'' general manager Ron Schueler said. ''He did the smart
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox wouldn't say for certain that Eldred was done.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the stuff hasn't come back, so that's not official, but as
a manager you have to go about and not plan for him to be back
again,'' Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we get him back, it would be great. From what I understand
they are waiting to get tests back from the doctors that could give
a glimmer of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Eldred would be the biggest blow yet to a starting
rotation that is struggling down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   James Baldwin, a 14-game winner, had to miss a start with a
tired arm and was rocked in his last outing. Jim Parque has won
only two of his last nine starts. And rookie Jon Garland, who's
been inconsistent, spent time on the disabled list after being hit
with a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, no Eldred, who brought more than just his pitching to the
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he completes a game and saves our bullpen and his
presence with the young pitchers on how to act, we lost a big part
of the team,'' Manuel said. ''He brings so much because he has been
through so much, so there is a lot to offer. And all those things
he has to offer, we will miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kip Wells, recalled Tuesday from a rehab assignment, said
Eldred was an influence on him during his first two stints with the
White Sox this season and during his rehab appearances at
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ''You see a lot of strength and perseverance in him you don't
see in a lot of other guys,'' Wells said. ''He was a little down
and upset that the course of action went the way it had. I think
it's more of an emotional letdown than a physical one. To have his
arm let him down a third or fourth time now is a little
disheartening for him and everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Eldred was not available for comment..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 2106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Avs Forward Weighing Contract  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- In an era when pro athletes pursue the security of
a long-term contract, Colorado Avalanche forward Chris Drury
apparently prefers to take things one year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Drury, a restricted free agent who had 20 goals and 47 assists
last season, has been offered a multiyear contract, but the former
Calder Trophy winner could be absent when the Avalanche report to
training camp on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Drury's Boston-based agent, Mark Witkin, said his client would
like to sign a one-year deal for the 2000-01 season. Drury, who
made $640,000 last year, would then be eligible for arbitration
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have made offers which really channel him into a
long-term deal,'' Witkin said Tuesday. ''In effect, they're saying,
'You have to go longer term,' and it's really what he doesn't want
to do. He wants the incentive of working hard every year and get a
contract based on what he contributed.''
</P>
<P>
   At only 24, Drury's best days are likely still ahead of him,
which would explain Colorado's desire to sign him to a long deal.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado general manager Pierre Lacroix, who does not discuss
ongoing contract negotiations, has been busy this summer.
</P>
<P>
   After re-signing key free agents Ray Bourque, Adam Deadmarsh,
Joe Sakic and Stephane Yelle, he has been trying to work out deals
with Drury and forward Milan Hejduk.
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk, who had 36 goals and 36 assists last year, also would
prefer a one-year deal. Attempts to reach his agent Tuesday were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche on Tuesday signed left wing Brad Larsen, 23, of
the American Hockey League Hershey Bears, and defenseman Stewart
Malgunas, 30, who played four games with Calgary last year. Terms
were not announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
