<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Calls U.S. a Rogue State  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) --North Korea on Tuesday accused the United
States of instigating an airport search of North Korean diplomats,
including the country's No. 2 leader, who angrily called off
participation in the U.N. Millennium summit and a New York meeting
with the president of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The incident Monday at the airport in Frankfurt, Germany, will
hurt U.S.-North Korean ties as well as slow reconciliation between
the two Koreas, the North Korean ambassador to the United Nations,
Li Hyong Chol, said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean Foreign Ministry warned in a statement that
''the United States will come to know what a dear price it will
have to pay for having hurt our people's dignity,'' but did not
specify whether or how it would retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of Kim Yong Nam, leader of the communist country's
parliament, to cancel his trip to New York was one of the first
setbacks to recent efforts by North and South Korea to do away with
decades of antagonism.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no indication the Pyongyang government planned to
halt its overall reconciliation policy. Also, Seoul officials view
plans for North Korean leader Kim Jong Il to visit South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung in Seoul as far more important than the
aborted New York meeting.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for that visit, which would be a followup
to a June summit between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's Kim said the airport incident was regrettable, but
should not hurt ''the trend of a thaw between the North and
South,'' according to his chief spokesman, Park-Jun-young.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is disappointed that the
North-South meeting is not taking place, but hopes there will be
continued progress toward normalization between the two countries,
said U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
   The airport dispute was reminiscent of other accusations by
North Korea that were apparently aimed at disrupting the close ties
between Seoul and its longtime ally, Washington, which keeps 37,000
troops in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the search, including a
pat-down of the diplomats and a luggage check, was partially a
result of misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a combination of unfamiliarity with our procedures and
I think some unfamiliarity on the part there (in Frankfurt) with
the delegation coming through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the United States had looked forward to North
Korean participation in the U.N. summit. ''We regret that they got
on a plane and headed back home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department said travelers from countries on a
U.S. terrorism watchlist have to undergo more stringent security
procedures, but that diplomats accredited to the United Nations and
Washington are exempt. The North Korean delegation, which did not
fall into either category, had not informed the United States that
it would be traveling on American Airlines, said a State Department
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Li, the North Korean ambassador, said the 15 North Korean
delegates were waiting to board an American Airlines flight to New
York when they were approached by U.S. aviation security officials.
The delegates were told they could not board unless they agreed to
what Li termed ''hooligan acts:'' answering questions, having their
luggage checked and undergoing a body search.
</P>
<P>
   Li said the delegates were strip searched, but Lockhart and
American Airlines denied that.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador said the aviation officials told the delegation
they were acting upon instructions ''they received from home.''
</P>
<P>
   When the delegation members protested and asked why they were
being searched, the security officials said that ''North Korea is
listed with other countries as a rogue state,'' the ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the U.N. summit, the North Korean leader was to have met
Kim Dae-jung to discuss further steps toward possible
reunification. The North Korean ambassador said he believed the
airport incident was intended to ''create obstacles'' in the
reconciliation process on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines apologized for the search. No U.S. government
agency participated in the search, American Airlines spokesman John
Hotard said from Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   However, the North Korean ambassador blamed the U.S. government
for the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''This incident is a fabricated scenario of the U.S.
administration,'' Li said. ''It is an insidious and brazen-faced
method of the United States. All these facts clearly show that the
United States is a rogue state.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is one of seven countries branded by the U.S. State
Department as a sponsor of terrorism. Under U.S. law, that bars all
but humanitarian aid to the North's government and rules out bank
loans from international financial organizations, which are heavily
influenced by Washington.	   The two nations recently held talks on possibly
removing the
communist country from the list. The U.S. State Department called
the meeting ''productive'' but did not disclose details.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang was put on the list because of its alleged involvement
in the bombing of a South Korean airliner in the skies near
Myanmar, also known as Burma, in 1987. All 115 people aboard the
Korean Air plane died.
</P>
<P>
   Ties between South and North Korea have improved dramatically in
recent months. Both sides stopped border propaganda broadcasts,
agreed to reconnect a cross-border railway and hold more reunions
of separate family members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
