<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Nominations Made in Fla.  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas led nine candidates in very early
returns as he sought a second term Tuesday after months of tumult
over the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 percent of precincts reporting, Penelas had 59 percent of
the vote. His nearest competitor had 19 percent. He must win a
majority to avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, in primaries in Florida and Nevada, candidates for
open Senate and House seats faced scant opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Democrat Bill Nelson and GOP Rep. Bill McCollum
easily won their parties' nominations for an open Senate seat,
setting up a competitive race in the fall with national importance.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas outraised his nearest competitor, county Commissioner
Miguel Diaz de la Portilla, by more than 4-to-1. Diaz de la
Portilla said Penelas ''split the community'' when he vowed that
local police would not help federal authorities return Elian to his
father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas later said police would help keep the peace, and has
emphasized ''healing the wounds'' left by the boy's case. The Elian
furor has not been a prominent part of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With half of Florida's precincts reporting, Nelson, the state
insurance commissioner, got 344,214 votes, or 77 percent, to win
the nomination to seek the seat of retiring GOP Sen. Connie Mack.
McCollum had 356,106 votes, or 82 percent, for his party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, who have made inroads in the South in recent
years, hope to take the Senate seat given up by Mack, who is
retiring after two terms.
</P>
<P>
   The seat left vacant by McCollum, a 10-term GOP member of
Congress who is hoping to succeed Mack, becomes part of the
national battle for control of the House, as does a Republican seat
left open by retiring four-term Rep. Tillie Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Bill Sublette and first-time candidate Ric Keller
split the GOP vote and went to a runoff for the nomination for
McCollum's seat near Orlando. The winner will face Democrat Linda
Chapin in November.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for Fowler's seat near Jacksonville, former Florida
Senate President Ander Crenshaw was leading in early returns in the
GOP primary. Retired motel owner-manager Tom Sullivan was leading
lawyer Kevin Schaun Sanders for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, Democratic Sen. Richard Bryan's decision to retire
after two terms set off a scramble. John Ensign, a veterinarian and
former two-term GOP congressman, faced two little-known candidates
in his bid for the Republican nomination. Ensign lost his 1998 bid
to unseat the state's senior senator, Democrat Harry Reid, by 428
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas lawyer Ed Bernstein has no primary opposition for the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Florida, allegations of racism rocked a contest for
sheriff. Rodney Moore, the black police chief of Quincy, is
challenging Sheriff W.A. Woodham, a white man in office for 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was arrested last month and charged with ticket-fixing and
other corruption. He, along with many of the state's top black
leaders, complained of racism. Gadsden County, west of Tallahassee
in the Panhandle, is the only Florida county with a majority black
population, about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With six of 16 precincts reporting, Woodham had 1,862 voters, or
57 percent, compared with Moore's 1,389 votes, or 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Democratic primary will face only nominal
opposition in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 2121 </TRAILER>
