<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Wing Works for Nomination  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Lawyers for a faction of the Reform
Party loyal to Pat Buchanan asked a state court Tuesday to declare
him the party's true presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Their rivals in the fractured party planned their own lawsuit
Wednesday seeking a legal judgment backing up their contention that
John Hagelin is the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   At stake: $12.6 million in federal subsidies for the winning
side.
</P>
<P>
   The action came six days after a federal judge in Lynchburg,
Va., refused to referee the party's bitter split, saying he lacked
the jurisdiction to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Cooter, an attorney for the Buchanan contingent, filed the
claim in Superior Court in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   That Los Angeles suburb was the site of the party's national
convention last month, when it split in two and produced dual
nominees. Cooter also filed the unsuccessful action in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Because Long Beach hosted the national convention, the state
court there should have jurisdiction over the party's actions
nationwide, Cooter said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Verney, a leader of the Hagelin faction, said his lawsuit
Wednesday would be based on the same premise.
</P>
<P>
   Cooter said he had not discussed the action Tuesday with
Buchanan or his campaign. He acted at the behest of Gerald Moan,
the chairman of the Reform Party wing aligned with Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The two camps have waged a battle to get their respective
nominees listed on ballots in the 50 states. Meanwhile, election
officials in Wisconsin are to announce Wednesday whether, and how,
Buchanan and Hagelin will be listed on the general election ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits come as both sides await a Federal Election
Commission ruling on the matter. That is likely to be appealed to a
federal court, Verney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
