<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yanks Williams Likely Out 4-6 Games  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE BRISENDINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- New York Yankees outfielder Bernie
Williams will likely miss 4-6 games because of recurring soreness
in his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said it doesn't feel as bad as it did the last time, which
is encouraging,'' manager Joe Torre said Tuesday before the second
game of a four-game series with the Kansas City Royals.
''Hopefully, maybe it was just something that was left over.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not planning on him for the rest of this trip, let's put
it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has 111 RBIs and needs 19 to tie the single-season
record for a switch-hitter, missed seven games from Aug. 19-25 with
strained muscles in his right rib cage, an injury sustained in
batting practice Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Williams hurt himself again swinging at a forkball
from Kansas City starter Mac Suzuki in the first inning of the
Yankees' 4-3 win. After striking out swinging to end the inning,
Williams played the bottom of the first in the outfield before
being replaced by Clay Bellinger.
</P>
<P>
   Williams dressed for batting practice Tuesday but did not take
any swings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll just be out there stretching, maybe doing some
shagging,'' he said. ''No swinging -- it's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Before getting hurt for the first time, Williams had started the
Yankees' first 118 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a durable player,'' Torre said. ''He's one of those guys
you just write in the lineup -- you don't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone might be joining the injured list, too. The
right-hander dislocated his left shoulder fielding a popped-up bunt
in the third inning Tuesday night and was taken to the hospital for
X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis was brighter for the return of second baseman
Chuck Knoblauch and reliever Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who has not played since returning from the disabled
list on Friday, said he hopes to return soon after being sidelined
since Aug. 3 with tendinitis in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling pretty good, which is encouraging,'' said
Knoblauch, whose stint on the DL was the first in his 10-year
career. ''I don't know that it will ever feel great the rest of the
year. I just have to deal with the fact that it's not feeling any
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch could start in another day or two, Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who has been plagued by tendinitis in his right
shoulder and has not pitched since July 29, threw more than 50
pitches in a simulated-game Monday. He could get some bullpen work
against Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's sore in all the appropriate places, and that's good,''
Torre said. ''I don't know about tomorrow, maybe Thursday. We'd
definitely like to have him get a game under his belt here.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Paul O'Neill continues to improve after missing
six games in late August with a right hip pointer. O'Neill made a
long run to grab Jermaine Dye's foul ball in the eighth inning of
Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a good play to get to that ball,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Yankees also called up LHP Randy Kiesler and INF
Alfonso Soriano from Triple-A Columbus. To make room for Kiesler on
the 40-man roster, the Yankees placed RHP Darrell Einertson on the
60-day DL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 2159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cuts 40 from Olympic Team  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- China is cutting 40 athletes and
officials from its team for the Sydney Olympics, including seven
rowers who failed blood tests for the banned performance-enhancing
drug EPO.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very pleased,'' International Olympic Committee president
Juan Antonio Samaranch said Wednesday of the doping withdrawals.
''I'm very happy. This is very good news. It shows the new system
for detecting doping substances will work very well. ... The
objective is to have clean games.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney organizers said they were notified by the Chinese Olympic
Committee of the withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   IOC medical director Patrick Schamasch received a letter from
the Chinese rowing association confirming that seven rowers were
being withdrawn from the Olympic team after they tested positive
for EPO, or erthyropoietin, during doping controls in China.
</P>
<P>
   Schamasch said blood tests showed the athletes' EPO levels were
above the allowable limit.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the IOC executive board approved the introduction of
a combined blood and urine test for EPO at the Sydney Games. EPO,
the drug of choice among endurance athletes, stimulates the
production of oxygen-carrying red blood cells, and experts say it
can improve performance by up to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, no test had been able to detect the use of synthetic
EPO.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, an athlete will be considered guilty of EPO use only
if both the blood and urine tests are positive. Schamasch said the
Chinese rowers were dropped based only on blood testing.
</P>
<P>
   China, tarnished by a series of doping scandals in swimming and
other sports, has been carrying out sweeping drug tests to prevent
the embarrassment of positive results during the Sydney Games. With
Beijing bidding for the 2008 Olympics, China is particularly eager
to be seen as cracking down.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Jianyong, secretary general of the Chinese Rowing
Association, said the rowers had withdrawn to protect their health
and uphold the fairness of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trusting the Chinese,'' Samaranch said. ''They are
fighting against doping. This is an example for many other
countries. This is good news for the image of sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the withdrawals of the 33 other Chinese team
members was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would be surprised if all 40 were (for drugs),'' IOC vice
president Dick Pound said. ''My guess is you'll find they were in
some elimination tournament and didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz, a former U.S. Olympic rower
and a vice president of the international rowing federation, said
the reduction in the Chinese team sent the right message to
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a warning to all athletes who wish to come to the
games with drugs in their system -- stay at home,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-05-00 2201 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000905.0185 </DOCNO>
