<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio prosecutor says Swango to plead guilty in New York deaths  </HEADLINE>
By LIZ SIDOTI
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) - Former physician Michael Swango is
expected to plead guilty to federal charges Wednesday in New York
that he killed three patients at a Long Island veterans' hospital,
Franklin County Prosecutor Ron O'Brien said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A federal indictment charged Swango in July with three counts of
murder, one count of assault, three counts of making false
statements and two counts of scheming to defraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's admitting to what he's charged with and that's it,''
O'Brien said. Swango, dubbed ''Dr. Death'' by tabloids, had pleaded
innocent to all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left for Swango's lawyer, Randi Chavis, on Tuesday were
not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in New York said Swango was expected in U.S
District Court on Wednesday. A court order prohibits them from
commenting further.
</P>
<P>
   A guilty plea to the three counts of murder would carry a
federal sentence of life in prison without parole, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also alleged Swango was responsible for Cynthia
Ann McGee's death on Jan. 14, 1984, and the poisoning of another
victim, Rena Cooper, at the Ohio State University hospital February
7, 1984. Cooper survived but was paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Swango's admission to those allegations would give the state
enough evidence to charge him with aggravated murder in the
poisoning of McGee, a 19-year-old gymnast, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will file that charge against Swango after he admits
to the federal charges, and Swango could answer to that charge in
Franklin County Common Pleas Court within the next two weeks,
O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will not pursue charges in Cooper's case because too
much time has passed under Ohio law.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the kind of thing he has done before that followed
him wherever he went,'' O'Brien said. ''We had suspicions about all
of the deaths. What we were missing was a level of evidence. We
could not bring charges against him in the McGee case without an
admission from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors claimed the only evidence previously available in
McGee's case was circumstantial. A nurse had told investigators
that Swango took a syringe into McGee's hospital room about an hour
before McGee's death to draw blood, which he never did, O'Brien
said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy concluded McGee died of pneumonia at the hospital
where Swango was an intern. Investigators since have found in
McGee's medical records that her potassium level spiked shortly
before her death, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The McGee family's attorney, Brian Miller, did not return a call
seeking comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Swango pleaded innocent to the three 1993 New York killings just
days before he was to be released from a federal prison in
Colorado. He was there on charges that he lied about his criminal
past to get his job at State University of New York at Stony Brook,
the medical school that ran the Veterans Affairs Hospital in
Northport where the deaths occurred.
</P>
<P>
   He is accused of injecting the three patients with toxins. In
two of the cases, he told hospital staff the patients' families had
issued ''do not resuscitate'' orders, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth patient also died of suspected poisoning, but
prosecutors said they had evidence only for an assault charge in
that case.
</P>
<P>
   Swango also is suspected of poisoning patients in Zimbabwe,
where he worked in 1994 after being fired by Stony Brook, and spent
30 months in prison in 1985 for poisoning six co-workers in Quincy,
Ill. No one died in that case.
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling book ''Blind Eye: The Story of a Doctor who Got
Away with Murder'' suggests Swango might have killed as many as 35
patients on two continents.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said it is unlikely that the number of people Swango
actually killed will be known.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without an admission from him, we don't have solid evidence in
any other cases,'' O'Brien said. ''And any other admission is not
going to be forthcoming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
