<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Vernon Dancer, a harness driver,
trainer and
breeder who was recently nominated for the sport's Hall of Fame,
died Tuesday. He was 77.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dancer drove in his first race in 1952. Among his best-known
trainees were the trotting filly Honeysuckle Rose, who won several
stakes races, and Tempered Yankee, who beat the top contenders of
his day.
</P>
<P>
   Dancer drove 1,723 winners, had earnings of $8.96 million and a
lifetime winning percentage of .395. His candidacy to the harness
racing Hall of Fame will be voted on this fall.
Elizabeth Gordon Norcross:
</P>
<P>
   FREDERICK, Md. (AP) -- Elizabeth Gordon Norcross, a former
editor-in-chief of House Beautiful magazine, died Sunday of
pneumonia. She was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Norcross, then known as Elizabeth Gordon, directed the editorial
content of the New York-based magazine from 1941 through 1964.
</P>
<P>
   She was a major proponent of architect Frank Lloyd Wright's work
and was inspired by Wright's practical, environmentally compatible
architecture. The magazine took its name from his book, ''The House
Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Norcross also is credited with introducing Shibui, a form of
Japanese design, to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote home maintenance columns for the Chicago Tribune, the
New York Herald Tribune and several other New York newspapers. She
also wrote a book, ''More House for Your Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Norcross was an honorary member of the American Institute of
Architecture and was knighted by the Finnish government for
promoting an exhibition of Scandinavian arts and crafts.
Willard Scott:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Willard ''Bubba'' Scott, a key defensive
player at Southern California in the late 1960s, died Friday of
cancer. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was one of the ''Wild Bunch,'' the nickname given to the
1969 Trojans' defensive line, which included Al Cowlings, Jimmy
Gunn, Charlie Weaver and Tody Smith. That team had a 10-0-1 record
and beat Michigan in the 1970 Rose Bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore, Scott was on the national championship team that
went 10-1 and defeated Indiana in the 1968 Rose Bowl. In Scott's
three years at Southern California, the Trojans had a 29-2-2
record.
Clyde Sukeforth:
</P>
<P>
   WALDOBORO, Maine (AP) -- Clyde Sukeforth, a former major league
catcher and Brooklyn Dodgers scout who helped set the stage for
Jackie Robinson to break baseball's color barrier, died Sunday. He
was 98.
</P>
<P>
   Sukeforth also scouted for the Pittsburgh Pirates and the
Atlanta Braves. Among the players he signed were Don Newcombe and
Roberto Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   Sukeforth was a confidant of Dodgers general manager Branch
Rickey, who sent him to Chicago in 1945 to watch a Negro League
game involving Robinson's Kansas City Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson sat out the game, but Sukeforth was impressed enough to
arrange the historic meeting with Rickey that led two years later
to Robinson becoming the first black to play in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Sukeforth was acting manager of the Dodgers, filling in for Leo
Durocher, on April 15, 1947, the day of Robinson's major league
debut. Brooklyn beat the Boston Braves, 5-3.
Jim Ward:
</P>
<P>
   SEMINOLE, Fla. (AP) -- Jim Ward, winner of two Ironman triathlons
in a senior division, died Monday after collapsing while cycling.
He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Ward was five miles into a 72-mile ride on the Pinellas Trail
with the St. Pete Mad Dog Triathlon Club when he fell.
</P>
<P>
   Ward began his career as a triathlete late in life and competed
in his first triathlon at the age of 68. He had been a foreign
service officer and led a guerrilla unit in combat as an Army
officer during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Ward completed more than 150 triathlons -- a 2.4-mile swim
followed by 112 miles on bicycle and a 26.2-mile marathon run. He
won in 1992 in the 75-and-over category and took the 75-plus title
in 1994 when he was 77, making him the event's oldest winner.
Audrey Wise:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Audrey Wise, a Labor Party member of Parliament
who remained a rebellious left-winger as the party shifted to the
center, died Saturday of a brain tumor. She was 65.
</P>
<P>
   She was elected in 1974, but lost her seat in Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative landslide in 1979. She was defeated again
in 1983, but finally returned to Parliament in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Labor Party's National Executive Committee
between 1982 and 1987, she was prominent in opposing leader Neil
Kinnock's efforts to purge the party of the ultra-left ''militant
tendency.''
</P>
<P>
   In her first term in Parliament, she co-authored an amendment
which forced James Callaghan's Labor government to link tax
allowances for the elderly to the rate of inflation. It was a major
defeat for the government and its Treasury chief, Denis Healy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Wise had remained fiercely independent,
frequently voting contrary to the party line in Parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
