<HEADLINE> Rangers 2, White Sox 1  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Chad Curtis hit a two-out RBI single in the ninth
inning Tuesday night as the Texas Rangers pushed across an unearned
run and beat the Chicago White Sox 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Rusty Greer reached to start the ninth when Chicago
shortstop Jose Valentin threw low to first for his 31st error of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   After a fielder's choice and fly out, Luis Alicea fouled off
four pitches from Bobby Howry (2-4) before singling and then Curtis
hit a 3-2 pitch to left to give the Rangers a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Johnson (1-0) pitched two shutout innings for his first
major league win and John Wetteland got three outs for his 30th
save.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's second straight loss to the Rangers dropped the White
Sox's lead over Cleveland to 6&AMP;frac12; games after the Indians beat Tampa
Bay on Tuesday night. It is the White Sox's smallest lead in the AL
Central since June 21.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox got a run off Darren Oliver in the fourth on
singles by Magglio Ordonez and Carlos Lee and a double-pay grounder
by Herbert Perry.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had five hits in the fifth but managed just one run
as Mike Sirotka struck out Rafael Palmeiro on a 3-2 pitch with the
bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee singled to start the inning and scored on a double
by Scott Sheldon, who was thrown out trying to stretch it into a
triple.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers then loaded the bases on a bunt and two infield hits
before Sirotka fanned Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka, bidding for his fourth straight win, went seven
innings, allowing eight hits and one run.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, making his first start since coming off the disabled
list and his first appearance since July 30, allowed six hits and a
run in six innings. He's been bothered most of the last three
months by weakness in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The game drew a small crowd of just 13,899. ... Oliver has
made eight rehab starts this season. ... Kip Wells, one of four
White Sox called up Tuesday, will start Wednesday's game. Wells is
in his third stint with the White Sox after beginning the season as
the No. 2 starter. ... Rusty Greer, scratched from Monday's lineup
with a stiff neck, didn't start again but pinch hit in the ninth.
... Wetteland's save gives him eight 30-save seasons and six
straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
