<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees 10, Royals 5  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE BRISENDINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- David Cone went down too early to get
the win, but reliever Dwight Gooden never lost the New York
Yankees' early lead Tuesday night in a 10-5 victory over the Kansas
City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9 hitter Jose Vizcaino went 4-for-5 and Scott Brosius hit an
eighth-inning grand slam for the Yankees, who maintained their
six-game lead over second-place Boston in the AL East. Brosius'
blast off reliever Andy Larkin splashed into the fountains beyond
left field and made it 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   Cone separated his left shoulder making a diving catch on Rey
Sanchez's bunt in the third inning, becoming the second Yankees
player in two days to go down with an injury. On Monday, center
fielder Bernie Williams aggravated a previous rib strain in the
first inning of a 4-3 win over the Royals. He is expected to miss
4-6 games.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden (6-4) replaced Cone and gave up three runs and seven hits
in 5 1-3 innings, walking one and striking out one. Mike Stanton
pitched the ninth, giving up Mike Sweeney's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's shoulder was popped back into place, but he was taken to
a hospital as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   David Justice homered and drove in two runs for the Yankees, who
beat Kansas City for the seventh time in eight games this season.
His leadoff homer in the seventh off reliever Paul Spoljaric gave
New York a 6-4 lead and atoned for a fielding error in the sixth
that allowed an unearned run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Beltran, making his first start since he went down with a
bruised knee on July 3, went 2-for-4 and drove in a run for the
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals took a 1-0 lead on Jermaine Dye's RBI double in the
first inning, but the Yankees scored four times in the third
against Jeff Suppan (7-9).
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger, Williams' replacement in center field, led off
with a home run to left center. Paul O'Neill's bases-loaded fly
ball, caught by a wind blowing in from right field, fell in for an
RBI single. Tino Martinez followed with a sacrifice fly for the
inning's first out.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill got hung up between first and second when Justice struck
out, but managed to elude the tag long enough for Derek Jeter to
score from third.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan gave up five runs and 10 hits in 5 1-3 innings, striking
out three and walking four.
</P>
<P>
   The teams traded sacrifice flies in the fifth, Johnny Damon
answering Justice's RBI with his own to make it 5-2. The Royals
scored twice in the sixth, cutting the Yankees' lead to 5-4, when
Beltran hit an RBI single to left and the ball got away from
Justice, allowing Mark Quinn to score.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Brosius' grand slam was his second of the season. He hit
the first on May 7 against Baltimore. ... Cone had won three of his
last four decisions after a 1-10 start. ... Justice's homer was his
35th of the season but his first since Aug. 19. ... Damon stole his
league-leading 41st base in the third. ... With a second-inning
walk, Jeter extended his streak of reaching base safely to 30
games, the most by a Yankee since he did it in 53 straight games
last year. ... Sweeney needs seven more RBIs to tie the team record
of 133, set by Hal McRae in 1992. ... Dye, who doubled once
Tuesday, has four in the first two games of the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
